{"title_page": "Stephanie Grisham", "text_new": "{{Short description|White House Press Secretary}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name = Stephanie Grisham\n|image = Stephanie Grisham.jpg\n|office = Chief of Staff to the [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]]\n|president = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start = April 7, 2020\n|term_end = \n|predecessor = [[Lindsay Reynolds]]\n|successor = \n|office1      = [[Office of the First Lady of the United States|Press Secretary to the First Lady]]\n|president1   = [[Donald Trump]]\n|1blankname1 = {{nowrap|First Lady}}\n|1namedata1 = [[Melania Trump]]\n|term_start1  = April 7, 2020\n|term_end1    =  \n|term_start2  = March 27, 2017\n|term_end2    = July 1, 2019\n|predecessor2 = [[Joanna Rosholm]]\n|office3 = 30th [[White House Press Secretary]]\n|president3 = Donald Trump\n|term_start3 = July 1, 2019\n|term_end3 = April 7, 2020\n|predecessor3 = [[Sarah Sanders]]\n|successor3 = [[Kayleigh McEnany]]\n|office4 = [[White House Communications Director]]\n|president4 = Donald Trump\n|term_start4 = July 1, 2019\n|term_end4 = April 7, 2020\n|predecessor4 = [[Bill Shine]]\n|successor4 = ''Vacant''\n|birth_name = Stephanie Ann Allen\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1976|07|23}}\n|birth_place = [[Colorado]], U.S.\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse = {{marriage|Dan Marries|1997|2004|reason=div.}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Todd Grisham]]|2004|2006|reason=div.}}\n|children = 2\n|education = [[Colorado Mesa University]]\n}}\n'''Stephanie Ann Grisham'''<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncwlife.com/eastmont-graduate-named-new-press-secretary-for-president-trump/ |title=Eastmont graduate named new press secretary for President Trump |last=FitzSimmons |first=Cal |date=June 25, 2019 |work=[[KWCC-LD|NCW Life Channel]] |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Allen'''; born July 23, 1976) is an American White House official who served as the 30th [[White House press secretary]] and as [[White House Communications Director|White House communications director]] from July 2019<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons /><ref name=krem_20190625_Carroll /><ref name=\"Fox\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/stephanie-grisham-to-become-new-white-house-press-secretary-flotus-announces |title=Stephanie Grisham to be the new White House Press Secretary|last=Pappas|first=Alex|date=June 25, 2019 |website=FoxNews.com |publisher=[[Fox News]] |access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> to April 2020.<ref name=\"CNN-Out\">{{Cite news |last=Collins |first=Kaitlan Collins |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary-briefing-melania-trump/index.html |title=Grisham out as West Wing press secretary without having held a briefing |date=April 7, 2020 |work=CNN |access-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Bennett |first2=Kate}}</ref> She is the first White House press secretary in American history to hold no press conferences,<ref name=\"Washington Post 2020\">{{cite web | title=The short, strange tale of Stephanie Grisham, Trump\u2019s third - and invisible - press secretary | website=Washington Post | date=2020-04-14 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/magazine/2020/04/14/short-strange-tale-trumps-former-press-secretary-stephanie-grisham/ | access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> instead opting for interviews on conservative news outlets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary-briefing-melania-trump/index.html|title=Grisham out as West Wing press secretary without having held a briefing|author1=Kaitlan Collins |author2=Kate Bennett|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/stephanie-grisham-white-house-press-secretary-donald-trump-1202902447/|title=Stephanie Grisham Departs As White House Press Secretary|last=Johnson|first=Ted|last2=Johnson|first2=Ted|date=2020-04-07|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/11/media/stephanie-grisham-briefings-fox/index.html|title=White House press secretary Stephanie Grisham has yet to hold a briefing with reporters, but finds time for Fox News |date=November 11, 2019 |first=Oliver |last=Darcy |publisher=CNN |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> She was a press aide to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]],<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2019/06/14/who-is-stephanie-grisham-bio/|title=Who Is Stephanie Grisham? She Just Replaced Sarah Sanders|last=Bach|first=Natasha|publisher=Fortune Magazine|date=June 14, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190625\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/us/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary.html |title=Trump Names Stephanie Grisham, Aide to First Lady, as Sarah Sanders's Successor |first1=Katie |last1=Rogers |first2=Annie |last2=Karni |date=June 25, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> and then a member of the presidential [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump|transition team]].<ref name=wapo_20190828>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/stephanie-grisham-is-trumps-communications-czar-only-most-people-wouldnt-know-it/2019/08/27/b79656ba-c44b-11e9-b5e4-54aa56d5b7ce_story.html |title=Stephanie Grisham is Trump's communications czar. Only most people wouldn't know it. |first=Paul |last=Farhi |date=August 28, 2019 |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"azr_20170119\">{{cite news|last1=Wingett Sanchez|first1=Yvonne |title=This Arizonan is going to the White House to work for Donald Trump |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/politicalinsider/2017/01/19/arizonan-white-house-stephanie-grisham-donald-trump/96797254/ |date=January 19, 2017 |work=[[Arizona Republic|The Republic]] |accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=azct_20190625_Howard>{{cite web |url=https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2019/06/25/trump-taps-stephanie-grisham-as-white-house-spokeswoman/ |title=Trump taps Stephanie Grisham as White House spokeswoman |first=Andrew |last=Howard |date=June 25, 2019 |newspaper=[[Arizona Capitol Times]] |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Grisham assumed the role of chief of staff to the First Lady on April 7, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-press-secretary-idUSKBN21P29Q|title=White House spokeswoman Grisham switches to first lady's staff|date=2020-04-07|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nStephanie Ann Allen was born in Colorado to Dave and Elizabeth Ann Allen, the middle child of three.<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons /><ref name=wapo_20190828 /> Her family are farmers.<ref name=wapo_20190828 />\n\nShe moved with her mother to [[East Wenatchee, Washington]], where she graduated from [[Eastmont High School]] in 1994.<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons /><ref name=krem_20190625_Carroll>{{cite web |url=https://www.krem.com/article/news/politics/new-white-house-press-secretary-has-ties-to-east-wenatchee/293-35cd4943-b0b7-467f-a34d-b021abe17f27 |title=New White House press secretary has ties to East Wenatchee |last=Carroll |first=Megan |date=June 25, 2019 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[KREM (TV)]] |access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> Her mother has since moved to Nebraska, where she is known as Ann Schroder.<ref name=azr_20190626>{{cite news |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2019/06/26/stephanie-grisham-path-new-white-house-press-secretary/1572350001/ |title=Stephanie Grisham's unlikely path from Arizona politics to White House press secretary |newspaper=[[Arizona Republic]] |first1=Yvonne |last1=Wingett Sanchez |first2=Ronald J |last2=Hansen |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGrisham began voting in Arizona as a registered Democrat in 1997.<ref name=azr_20190626 />\n\nAs Stephanie Ann Sommerville, she married Danny Don Marries in Nevada on April 7, 1997.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=Heavy_20190626_McBride>{{cite web |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/stephanie-grisham-husband-married/ |title=Is Stephanie Grisham Married? Learn About Her Ex Husband |last=McBride |first=Jessica |date=June 26, 2019 |work=Heavy.com |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> They met at [[Mesa State College]] in [[Grand Junction, Colorado]].<ref name=star_20130707>{{cite web |url=https://tucson.com/entertainment/television/we-ve-said-our-goodbyes-kold-anchor-posts-his-pain/article_601cf165-1bd7-5e85-be6b-b59e0e46f6d2.html |title='We've said our goodbyes:' KOLD anchor posts his pain |first=Cathalena E |last=Burch |work=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |date=July 7, 2013 |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> They had a son in June 1998, and her husband joined [[KOLD-TV]] as a news anchor in [[Tucson, Arizona]], on the day after their son's first birthday.<ref name=Heavy_20190626_McBride /><ref name=star_20130707 /> They divorced in 2004.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=sentinel_20190626>{{cite news |url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/local/report/062519_grisham_trump/ex-tucsonan-grisham-named-press-secretary-president-trump/ |title=Ex-Tucsonan Grisham named press secretary for President Trump |first=Dylan |last=Smith |date=June 25, 2019 |website=[[TucsonSentinel.com]] |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Swift>{{cite news |first=Gillian |last=Walters |url=https://www.nickiswift.com/157527/the-untold-truth-of-stephanie-grisham |title=The Untold Truth of Stephanie Gresham |date=July 3, 2019 |website=[[Nicki Swift]] |accessdate=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2004, she subsequently married [[Todd Grisham]], a KOLD sportscaster. They divorced in 2006.<ref name=sentinel_20190626 />\n\nAround 2008, she had a second son.<ref name=Heavy_20190626_McBride/>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing her divorce(s), Grisham was the spokeswoman for [[American Automobile Association|AAA]] Arizona in 2007,<ref name=sentinel_20170327>{{cite web |url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/local/report/032717_grisham/ex-tucsonan-named-spokeswoman-first-lady-melania-trump/|title=Ex-Tucsonan named spokeswoman for first lady Melania Trump |first=Dylan |last=Smith|date=March 27, 2017 |website=TucsonSentinel.com|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> but was fired within a year after being accused of cheating on expense reports.<ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\">{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=Elizabeth |title=Stephanie Grisham's Turbulent Ascent to a Top White House Role |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/22/us/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary.html |work=The New York Times |date=August 22, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913183259/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/22/us/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary.html |archivedate=September 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Grisham was fired from a subsequent job at ad agency Mindspace over plagiarism charges, copying AAA material verbatim into her client's web page.<ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" />\n\nFrom 2008 to 2010, Grisham worked as a spokeswoman for the [[Arizona Charter Schools Association]].<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" /> There she met [[Tom Horne]], Arizona's superintendent of public schools.<ref name=azr_20190626 />\n\nCirca 2011 to 2014, Grisham served as spokeswoman for Tom Horne after he was elected Arizona attorney general.<ref name=azr_20190626 /> She witnessed the [[execution of Joseph Wood]] and controversially claimed that the two hour ordeal had been \"quite peaceful\" despite contrary observations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-nn-arizona-execution-20140723-story.html|title=Arizona killer takes 2 hours to die, fueling lethal-injection debate - Los Angeles Times|first1=Matt |last1=Pearce |first2=Cindy |last2=Carcamo |first3=Maya |last3=Srikrishnan |date=July 23, 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a29508/another-execution-horror-story/|title=It's Time to End Our State-Sponsored Barbarism |first=Charles P |last=Pierce |date=July 24, 2014 |magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=azr_20190625>{{cite news |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2019/06/25/white-house-press-secretary-stephanie-grisham-had-controversial-arizona-career/1559269001/ |title=Stephanie Grisham, new White House press secretary, had controversial Arizona career |newspaper=[[Arizona Republic]] |first1=Yvonne |last1=Wingett Sanchez |first2=Ronald J |last2=Hansen |date=June 25, 2019 |accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Grisham also worked for [[Mitt Romney]]'s [[Mitt Romney 2012 presidential campaign|2012 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"fox10phoenix\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fox10phoenix.com/news/arizona-news/single-mother-from-the-valley-working-for-the-trump-white-house |title=Single mother from the Valley working for the Trump White House |first=Kari |last=Lake |date=June 25, 2017 |publisher=[[KSAZ-TV]] |website=fox10phoenix.com |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/>\n\nAfter Republican [[Mark Brnovich]] defeated Horne in the 2014 GOP primary, Grisham worked as a spokesperson for the [[Arizona House of Representatives]] Republican caucus.<ref name=azr_20190626 /> She revoked the [[Arizona Capitol Times]]'s press credentials hours after their reporting that the House speaker, [[David Gowan]], had traveled at state taxpayers' expense during his campaign for Congress.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=azct_20160408_Small>{{cite web |url=https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2016/04/08/this-new-background-check-policy-is-only-the-latest-retaliation-from-gowans-house/ |title=This new background check policy is only the latest retaliation from Gowan's House |first=Jim |last=Small |date=April 8, 2016 |newspaper=Arizona Capitol Times |accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref> Reporters refused to comply, and Gowan rescinded the order.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" />\n\nIn September 2015, Grisham worked as a press coordinator for [[Pope Francis's 2015 visit to North America#26 September (New York City, Philadelphia)|Pope Francis's visit to Philadelphia]] as an independent contractor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/politicalinsider/2015/09/25/arizona-house-spokeswoman-prepping-pope/72826188/ |title=Arizona House spokeswoman prepping for the pope |first=Mary Jo |last=Pitzl |date=September 26, 2015 |work=The Republic |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Trump campaign and transition===\nCirca August 2015, Grisham started working as a press aide to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/><ref name=\"azr_20170119\"/> She helped arrange his campaign stops in Phoenix and around the state and region throughout the primary, a role that quickly expanded to include his rallies around the U.S.<ref name=\"azr_20170119\"/> Grisham was on state payroll until May 2016, when she took an unpaid leave from the Arizona House of Representatives to work on Trump's campaign.<ref name=azct_20190625_Howard /><ref name=\"knau_20161201\">{{cite web|url=http://www.knau.org/post/trump-names-house-pr-person-staff-treasurer-adviser |title=Trump Names House PR Person To Staff, Treasurer As Adviser |date=December 1, 2016  |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[KNAU]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter his victory, Grisham was named a special adviser for operations and served on Trump's transition team.<ref name=\"azr_20170119\"/><ref name=\"knau_20161201\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1047287/sb/ALL/3|title=Schedule B for ALL Line|website=docquery.fec.gov |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1135946/sb/23/3|title=Schedule B for Line|website=docquery.fec.gov|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1148952/sb/ALL/5|title=Schedule B for ALL Line|website=docquery.fec.gov |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> Arizona House speaker David Gowan paid her $19,000 in state salary over an 8-week period while she was serving as a member of the Trump transition team.<ref name=azct_20190625_Howard /><ref name=azct_20170425_Stephenson>{{cite web |url=https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2017/04/25/tradition-dictates-no-show-no-problem-in-house-transition/ |title=FLOTUS spokeswoman Stephanie Grisham on state payroll while on Trump's victory tour and transition team |first=Hank |last=Stephenson |date=April 25, 2017 |newspaper=Arizona Capitol Times |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Trump administration===\nAfter Trump's January 2017 inauguration, Grisham was named deputy press secretary for [[Sean Spicer]] in the West Wing of the White House.<ref name=\"fox10phoenix\"/><ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, First Lady Melania Trump moved her over to the East Wing.<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/><ref name=sentinel_20170327 /> A former White House colleague said that the president regretted losing Grisham to the first lady's office because of Grisham's loyalty and skill at handling the press while acting as his traveling press secretary. During that time, she built relationships with many reporters at events. Despite losing Grisham as part of his own staff, President Trump said he was satisfied that the first lady would \"be in good hands\". Grisham was described by several sources who had worked with her previously as being \"highly competent\" and \"self-aware\"; some suggested that she enjoyed \"trolling the press.\" <ref name=\"Beast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-white-house-wont-stop-melania-from-contradicting-trump|title=The White House Won't Stop Melania From Contradicting Trump|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|last=Markay|first=Lachlan|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Office of Special Counsel]] stated that Grisham violated the [[Hatch Act of 1939]] following a complaint by Senator [[Tom Carper]]. Grisham was accused of using her official [[Twitter]] account on July 11, 2018, to tweet out Trump's campaign slogan. Violation of the act is not a crime, but a workplace guideline, and the agency responded by sending Grisham a warning letter.<ref name=\"Hatch\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/melania-trump-spokesperson-violate-hatch-act-1132130|title=Melania Trump's Spokeswoman Stephanie Grisham Violated Hatch Act With 'Make America Great Again' Tweet|last=Hutzler|first=Alexandra|work=[[Newsweek]] |date=October 9, 2018|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Grisham replaced [[Sarah Sanders]] as [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]] and [[White House Communications Director|White House communications director]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-grisham-idUSKCN1TQ29I|title=Longtime Trump aide Stephanie Grisham will succeed Sanders as press secretary |first=Steve |last=Holland |date=June 25, 2019 |agency=Reuters |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> Grisham's appointment was announced by Melania Trump via [[Twitter]] on June 25, 2019.<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\" /><ref name=cnn_20190625>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary/index.html?no-st=1568740491|title=Trump taps Melania Trump's spokeswoman as next White House press secretary|publisher=CNN|last=Bennett|first=Kate|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref> The June 28, 2019 ''Annual Report to Congress on White House Office Personnel'' listed Grisham as \"Assistant to the President and Deputy Chief of Staff for Communications for the First Lady\", with an annual salary of $183,000.00.<ref name=ReportWHpersonnel_20190629>{{cite web |title=Annual Report to Congress on White House Personnel |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/July-1-2019-Report-FINAL.pdf |website=whitehouse.gov |publisher=Executive Office of the President |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830034415/https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/July-1-2019-Report-FINAL.pdf |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |date=June 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2019, the ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' published an opinion piece written by Grisham and her deputy [[Hogan Gidley]] entitled, \"The ''Washington Post''{{'}}s lost summer.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/op-eds/the-washington-posts-lost-summer|title=The Washington Post's lost summer |first1=Stephanie |last1=Grisham |first2=Hogan |last2=Gidley |date=September 5, 2019 |website=[[Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref> The authors asserted the ''Post'' had not reported on several Trump accomplishments that the paper actually did report. In one instance, the piece linked to a ''Post'' story entitled \"Trump becomes first sitting president to set foot into North Korea\" as the authors asserted the paper had not reported the event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mediaite.com/trump/white-house-press-secretaries-publish-op-ed-claiming-washington-post-didnt-cover-stories-the-paper-actually-did-cover/|title=Stephanie Grisham Claims ''Washington Post'' Didn't Cover Stories the Paper Actually Did Cover |first=Connor |last=Mannion |date=September 6, 2019 |work=[[Mediaite]] |accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2019, when asked by the hosts of Fox & Friends if the White House planned to resume its daily press briefing Grisham said \"not right now... I mean, ultimately, if the president decides that it's something we should do, we can do that, but right now he's doing just fine. And to be honest, the briefings have become a lot of theater. And I think that a lot of reporters were doing it to get famous. I mean, yeah, they're writing books now. I mean, they're all getting famous off of this presidency. And so, I think it's great what we're doing now.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2mymMUR|title=White House press secretary says daily briefings aren't coming back any time soon|last=Forgey|first=Quint|date=September 23, 2019 |website=[[POLITICO]] |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2019, appearing on Fox & Friends, Grisham defended Trump's description of \"Never Trump Republicans\" as \"Human scum\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1187063301731209220?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed&ref_url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/press-secretary-stephanie-grisham-trump-human-scum|title=The Never Trumper Republicans, though on respirators with not many left, are in certain ways worse and more dangerous for our Country than the Do Nothing Democrats. Watch out for them, they are human scum!|last=Trump|first=Donald J.|date=October 23, 2019|website=@realDonaldTrump|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>  When asked if Trump should apologize, Grisham said \"No, no, he shouldn't. The people who are against him and who have been against him and working against his [agenda] since the day they took office are just that. It is horrible that people are working against a president who is delivering results for this country and has been since day one. And, the fact that people continue to try to negate anything he's been trying to do and take away from the good work he's doing on behalf of the American people, they deserve strong language like that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/press-secretary-stephanie-grisham-trump-human-scum|title=Press secretary Grisham on Trump's 'human scum' tweet: Those working against him are 'just that'|last=Musto|first=Julia|date=October 24, 2019|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, 2019, in response to criticism of President Trump by his former chief of staff Gen. [[John F. Kelly]] (Ret.) Grisham stated: \"I worked with John Kelly, and he was totally unequipped to handle the genius of our President.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/26/john-kelly-trump-impeachment-yes-man-058450|title=White House hits back at John Kelly over impeachment remarks|last=Semones|first=Evan |date=October 26, 2019 |website=POLITICO |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2019, during the testimony of [[William B. Taylor Jr.]], Grisham commented that the [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]] was a \"sham hearing\" that is \"not only boring, it is a colossal waste of taxpayer time & money.\"<ref name=RollCall_20191113>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/whitehouse/white-house-claims-trump-too-busy-to-watch-boring-impeachment-hearing |title=White House says Trump 'too busy' to watch 'boring' impeachment hearing |first=John T |last=Bennett |date=November 13, 2019 |newspaper=[[Roll Call]] |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=nytimes_20191113>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/13/us/politics/trump-impeachment.html |title=Full Video and Analysis of Day 1 of Impeachment Hearing Testimony |date=November 13, 2019 |website=New York Times |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=RollCall_20191113 />\n\nThat same month, Grisham claimed that Obama administration officials had left \"you will fail\" notes for the incoming Trump administration officials. Numerous Obama administration officials rejected the claim. Grisham ultimately retracted her assertion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/nov/20/stephanie-grisham-obama-officials-you-will-fail-notes-claim|title=Trump press secretary backtracks claim Obama officials left 'You will fail' notes|last=Gabbatt|first=Adam|date=November 20, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 22, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Grisham defended President Trump's implication that former congressman [[John Dingell]] was in hell. She described Trump as a \"counter-puncher\" who was \"under attack.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-press-secretary-president-trump-suggested-late/story?id=67821688|title=White House defends Trump as 'counter-puncher' after he suggests late Michigan congressman in hell|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/19/white-house-defends-trumps-attack-on-dead-lawmaker-john-dingell/ |title=White House defends Trump's attack on dead lawmaker John Dingell |first=Bob |last=Fredericks |date=December 19, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |access-date=January 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, it was announced that Grisham left her role as White House Press Secretary and returned to the East Wing to serve as Melania Trump's chief of staff,<ref name=\"CNN-Out\" /> effective that same day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Zilbermints |first=Regina |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/491525-grisham-leaves-role-as-white-house-press-secretary |title=Grisham leaves role as White House press secretary |date=April 7, 2020 |work=The Hill |access-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Briefing controversy===\nAs of March 11, 2020, Grisham had not conducted a formal press briefing in 365 days.<ref name=cnn_20200311>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/white-house-press-briefing-one-year/index.html |title=Make sure to remember this appalling 1-year anniversary |first=Chris |last=Cillizza |date=March 11, 2020 |work=The Point with Chris Cillizza |publisher=CNN |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=nyt_20200110>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/10/business/media/stephanie-grisham-trump-press-secretary.html |title=Stephanie Grisham: Trump's Press Secretary Who Doesn't Meet the Press |date=January 10, 2020 |first1=Michael M. |last1=Grynbaum |first2=Katie |last2=Rogers |newspaper=New York Times |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> However, she appeared on Fox News, Fox Business Network, [[One America News Network]], and the Sinclair Broadcast Group many times during the same period.<ref name=wapo_20200111 /><ref name=nyt_20200110 /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/11/media/stephanie-grisham-briefings-fox/index.html|title=White House press secretary Stephanie Grisham has yet to hold a briefing with reporters, but finds time for Fox News |date=November 11, 2019 |first=Oliver |last=Darcy |publisher=CNN |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]'' devoted two prime-time segments in one week to question whether taxpayers should pay her $183,000 salary,<ref name=nyt_20200110 /> and her hypocrisy.<ref name=cnn_20200110>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/01/10/stephanie-grisham-again-ridiculist-sot-ac360-vpx.cnn/video/playlists/ac360-videos/ |title=Cooper to WH press sec.: Your secret is safe with us |first=Anderson |last=Cooper |date=January 10, 2020 |work=The Ridiculist |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> \"Miss Grisham has gone from 'we are human beings' to 'they are human scum.' ... It's actually really kind of sad....\"<ref name=cnn_20200107>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/01/07/stephanie-grisham-press-briefings-ridiculist-sot-pkg-ac360-vpx.cnn/video/playlists/ac360-videos/ |title=Cooper calls out White House over lack of press briefings |first=Anderson |last=Cooper |date=January 7, 2020 |work=The Ridiculist |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anderson-cooper-stephanie-grisham-hypocrisy_n_5e143513c5b6b5a713bfeef9 |title=Anderson Cooper Nails Hypocrisy Of Trump Press Secretary Stephanie Grisham |first=Lee |last=Moran |date=January 7, 2020 |website=[[HuffPost]] |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/anderson-cooper-stephanie-grisham-cnn-responds-white-house-press-secretary-2020-1 |title=Anderson Cooper doubled down in his feud with White House press secretary Stephanie Grisham, calling her statements 'kind of sad' |first=Kat |last=Tenbarge |date=January 7, 2020 |website=Business Insider |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Her \"unintentionally ironic and deeply hypocritical\" social media statements and infrequent televised interviews \"appear meant to defend the president but actually point out the president's own failings.\"<ref name=cnn_20200110 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anderson-cooper-stephanie-grisham-subverting-trump_n_5e182730c5b650c621dc40ca |title=Anderson Cooper Has A Theory About Stephanie Grisham Secretly Working Against Trump |first=Lee |last=Moran |date=January 10, 2020 |website=[[HuffPost]] |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>  Margaret Sullivan has commented in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' that Grisham \"may hold the title but she's not doing the job\".<ref name=wapo_20200111>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/stephanie-grisham-is-not-the-worst-ever-white-house-press-secretary-heres-why/2020/01/10/405340bc-33be-11ea-a053-dc6d944ba776_story.html |title=Stephanie Grisham is not the worst-ever White House press secretary. Here's why. |first=Margaret |last=Sullivan |date=January 11, 2020 |newspaper=Washington Post |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAuthors [[Don Winslow]] and [[Stephen King]] pledged to donate $100,000 each to charity after Grisham held a 60-minute briefing answering questions from the White House press corps.<ref name=wapo_20200111 /><ref name=nyt_20200110 /> Also, 13 former White House and military press secretaries from three administrations before Trump published a letter calling for the restoration of press briefings.<ref name=wapo_20200111 /><ref name=nyt_20200110 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/10/opinions/ex-press-secretaries-open-letter-on-press-briefings/index.html |title=Why America needs to hear from its government |date=January 10, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> The press briefings never occurred.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gearan |first=Anne |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/stephanie-grisham-out-as-white-house-press-secretary-after-eight-months-during-which-she-held-no-regular-news-briefings/2020/04/07/6d93b7aa-75bd-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html |title=Stephanie Grisham out as White House press secretary after eight months during which she held no regular news briefings |date=April 7, 2020 |work=Washington Post |access-date=April 12, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=HouseEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow |first2=closeAnne GearanWhite House reporterEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollowJosh Dawsey closeJosh DawseyReporter covering the White |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents of driving while intoxicated==\nOn January 9, 2013, Grisham was pulled over for speeding in [[Gilbert, Arizona|Gilbert]], [[Maricopa County, Arizona]]. The officer observed Grisham's signs of intoxication, and she failed a field sobriety test. Grisham denied consuming any alcohol, but said she had taken a [[Xanax]] 90 minutes earlier and a [[Zoloft]] the prior night. A blood test revealed Grisham's blood alcohol content to be .105 percent, which is above the .08 legal limit in Arizona. She also was found to be driving on a suspended license since August 2012 for failure to answer a traffic citation. In August 2014, Grisham accepted a plea bargain agreement that reduced the charge to misdemeanor reckless driving, plus two years of probation.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190625\" /><ref name=\"tsg_20190828\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/buster/arizona/press-secretary-collars-162053|title=Like So Many Of His Associates, Donald Trump's New Press Secretary Has Posed For Some Mug Shots|date=August 28, 2019|website=The Smoking Gun|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> She returned to court twice for failure to pay the $779 in fines and failure to complete a [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] program.<ref name=azr_20190626 />\n\nShortly after midnight, December 5, 2015, Grisham was arrested again in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Maricopa County, Arizona]] for driving without her headlights and suspicion of [[driving under the influence]]; thus violating her probation.<ref name=azr_20190626 /> Grisham failed to appear at her court hearing on January 19, 2016,<ref name=azr_20190626 /> whereupon the judge issued a warrant for her arrest.<ref name=\"tsg_20190828\" /> Afterwards, Grisham pleaded guilty.  In July 2016, she was ordered into a treatment program and to pay nearly $1,600 in court costs and fines.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190625\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" /><ref name=\"tsg_20190828\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/tag/stephanie+grisham/ Stephanie Grisham] at ''[[TucsonSentinel.com]]''\n* [https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/tag/stephanie-grisham/ Stephanie Grisham] at the ''[[Arizona Capitol Times]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/meet-melania-trumps-enforcer-its-not-her-husband/2018/12/07/52a5a864-f8c7-11e8-863c-9e2f864d47e7_story.html/ Stephanie Grisham] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bill Shine]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Communications Director|White House Director of Communications]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sarah Sanders]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Press Secret