4|reason=div.}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Todd Grisham]]|2004|2006|reason=div.}}\n|children = 2\n|education = [[Colorado Mesa University]]\n}}\n'''Stephanie Ann Grisham'''<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncwlife.com/eastmont-graduate-named-new-press-secretary-for-president-trump/ |title=Eastmont graduate named new press secretary for President Trump |last=FitzSimmons |first=Cal |date=June 25, 2019 |work=[[KWCC-LD|NCW Life Channel]] |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> ([[n\u00e9e]] '''Allen'''; born July 23, 1976) is an American White House official who served as the 30th [[White House press secretary]] and as [[White House Communications Director|White House communications director]] from July 2019<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons /><ref name=krem_20190625_Carroll /><ref name=\"Fox\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/stephanie-grisham-to-become-new-white-house-press-secretary-flotus-announces |title=Stephanie Grisham to be the new White House Press Secretary|last=Pappas|first=Alex|date=June 25, 2019 |website=FoxNews.com |publisher=[[Fox News]] |access-date=June 25, 2019}}</ref> to April 2020.<ref name=\"CNN-Out\">{{Cite news |last=Collins |first=Kaitlan Collins |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary-briefing-melania-trump/index.html |title=Grisham out as West Wing press secretary without having held a briefing |date=April 7, 2020 |work=CNN |access-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Bennett |first2=Kate}}</ref> She is the first White House press secretary in American history to hold no press conferences,<ref name=\"Washington Post 2020\">{{cite web | title=The short, strange tale of Stephanie Grisham, Trump\u2019s third - and invisible - press secretary | website=Washington Post | date=2020-04-14 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/magazine/2020/04/14/short-strange-tale-trumps-former-press-secretary-stephanie-grisham/ | access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> instead opting for interviews on conservative news outlets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary-briefing-melania-trump/index.html|title=Grisham out as West Wing press secretary without having held a briefing|author1=Kaitlan Collins |author2=Kate Bennett|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/stephanie-grisham-white-house-press-secretary-donald-trump-1202902447/|title=Stephanie Grisham Departs As White House Press Secretary|last=Johnson|first=Ted|last2=Johnson|first2=Ted|date=2020-04-07|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/11/media/stephanie-grisham-briefings-fox/index.html|title=White House press secretary Stephanie Grisham has yet to hold a briefing with reporters, but finds time for Fox News |date=November 11, 2019 |first=Oliver |last=Darcy |publisher=CNN |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> She was a press aide to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]],<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\">{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2019/06/14/who-is-stephanie-grisham-bio/|title=Who Is Stephanie Grisham? She Just Replaced Sarah Sanders|last=Bach|first=Natasha|publisher=Fortune Magazine|date=June 14, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190625\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/us/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary.html |title=Trump Names Stephanie Grisham, Aide to First Lady, as Sarah Sanders's Successor |first1=Katie |last1=Rogers |first2=Annie |last2=Karni |date=June 25, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> and then a member of the presidential [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump|transition team]].<ref name=wapo_20190828>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/stephanie-grisham-is-trumps-communications-czar-only-most-people-wouldnt-know-it/2019/08/27/b79656ba-c44b-11e9-b5e4-54aa56d5b7ce_story.html |title=Stephanie Grisham is Trump's communications czar. Only most people wouldn't know it. |first=Paul |last=Farhi |date=August 28, 2019 |newspaper=[[Washington Post]] |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"azr_20170119\">{{cite news|last1=Wingett Sanchez|first1=Yvonne |title=This Arizonan is going to the White House to work for Donald Trump |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/politicalinsider/2017/01/19/arizonan-white-house-stephanie-grisham-donald-trump/96797254/ |date=January 19, 2017 |work=[[Arizona Republic|The Republic]] |accessdate=January 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name=azct_20190625_Howard>{{cite web |url=https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2019/06/25/trump-taps-stephanie-grisham-as-white-house-spokeswoman/ |title=Trump taps Stephanie Grisham as White House spokeswoman |first=Andrew |last=Howard |date=June 25, 2019 |newspaper=[[Arizona Capitol Times]] |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Grisham assumed the role of chief of staff to the First Lady on April 7, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-press-secretary-idUSKBN21P29Q|title=White House spokeswoman Grisham switches to first lady's staff|date=2020-04-07|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nStephanie Ann Allen was born in Colorado to Dave and Elizabeth Ann Allen, the middle child of three.<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons /><ref name=wapo_20190828 /> Her family are farmers.<ref name=wapo_20190828 />\n\nShe moved with her mother to [[East Wenatchee, Washington]], where she graduated from [[Eastmont High School]] in 1994.<ref name=ncwlife_20190625_FitzSimmons /><ref name=krem_20190625_Carroll>{{cite web |url=https://www.krem.com/article/news/politics/new-white-house-press-secretary-has-ties-to-east-wenatchee/293-35cd4943-b0b7-467f-a34d-b021abe17f27 |title=New White House press secretary has ties to East Wenatchee |last=Carroll |first=Megan |date=June 25, 2019 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[KREM (TV)]] |access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> Her mother has since moved to Nebraska, where she is known as Ann Schroder.<ref name=azr_20190626>{{cite news |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2019/06/26/stephanie-grisham-path-new-white-house-press-secretary/1572350001/ |title=Stephanie Grisham's unlikely path from Arizona politics to White House press secretary |newspaper=[[Arizona Republic]] |first1=Yvonne |last1=Wingett Sanchez |first2=Ronald J |last2=Hansen |date=June 27, 2019 |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGrisham began voting in Arizona as a registered Democrat in 1997.<ref name=azr_20190626 />\n\nAs Stephanie Ann Sommerville, she married Danny Don Marries in Nevada on April 7, 1997.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=Heavy_20190626_McBride>{{cite web |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/06/stephanie-grisham-husband-married/ |title=Is Stephanie Grisham Married? Learn About Her Ex Husband |last=McBride |first=Jessica |date=June 26, 2019 |work=Heavy.com |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> They met at [[Mesa State College]] in [[Grand Junction, Colorado]].<ref name=star_20130707>{{cite web |url=https://tucson.com/entertainment/television/we-ve-said-our-goodbyes-kold-anchor-posts-his-pain/article_601cf165-1bd7-5e85-be6b-b59e0e46f6d2.html |title='We've said our goodbyes:' KOLD anchor posts his pain |first=Cathalena E |last=Burch |work=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |date=July 7, 2013 |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> They had a son in June 1998, and her husband joined [[KOLD-TV]] as a news anchor in [[Tucson, Arizona]], on the day after their son's first birthday.<ref name=Heavy_20190626_McBride /><ref name=star_20130707 /> They divorced in 2004.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=sentinel_20190626>{{cite news |url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/local/report/062519_grisham_trump/ex-tucsonan-grisham-named-press-secretary-president-trump/ |title=Ex-Tucsonan Grisham named press secretary for President Trump |first=Dylan |last=Smith |date=June 25, 2019 |website=[[TucsonSentinel.com]] |accessdate=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Swift>{{cite news |first=Gillian |last=Walters |url=https://www.nickiswift.com/157527/the-untold-truth-of-stephanie-grisham |title=The Untold Truth of Stephanie Gresham |date=July 3, 2019 |website=[[Nicki Swift]] |accessdate=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2004, she subsequently married [[Todd Grisham]], a KOLD sportscaster. They divorced in 2006.<ref name=sentinel_20190626 />\n\nAround 2008, she had a second son.<ref name=Heavy_20190626_McBride/>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing her divorce(s), Grisham was the spokeswoman for [[American Automobile Association|AAA]] Arizona in 2007,<ref name=sentinel_20170327>{{cite web |url=http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/local/report/032717_grisham/ex-tucsonan-named-spokeswoman-first-lady-melania-trump/|title=Ex-Tucsonan named spokeswoman for first lady Melania Trump |first=Dylan |last=Smith|date=March 27, 2017 |website=TucsonSentinel.com|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> but was fired within a year after being accused of cheating on expense reports.<ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\">{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=Elizabeth |title=Stephanie Grisham's Turbulent Ascent to a Top White House Role |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/22/us/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary.html |work=The New York Times |date=August 22, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913183259/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/22/us/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary.html |archivedate=September 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Grisham was fired from a subsequent job at ad agency Mindspace over plagiarism charges, copying AAA material verbatim into her client's web page.<ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" />\n\nFrom 2008 to 2010, Grisham worked as a spokeswoman for the [[Arizona Charter Schools Association]].<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" /> There she met [[Tom Horne]], Arizona's superintendent of public schools.<ref name=azr_20190626 />\n\nCirca 2011 to 2014, Grisham served as spokeswoman for Tom Horne after he was elected Arizona attorney general.<ref name=azr_20190626 /> She witnessed the [[execution of Joseph Wood]] and controversially claimed that the two hour ordeal had been \"quite peaceful\" despite contrary observations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-nn-arizona-execution-20140723-story.html|title=Arizona killer takes 2 hours to die, fueling lethal-injection debate - Los Angeles Times|first1=Matt |last1=Pearce |first2=Cindy |last2=Carcamo |first3=Maya |last3=Srikrishnan |date=July 23, 2014 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/politics/a29508/another-execution-horror-story/|title=It's Time to End Our State-Sponsored Barbarism |first=Charles P |last=Pierce |date=July 24, 2014 |magazine=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=azr_20190625>{{cite news |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/arizona/2019/06/25/white-house-press-secretary-stephanie-grisham-had-controversial-arizona-career/1559269001/ |title=Stephanie Grisham, new White House press secretary, had controversial Arizona career |newspaper=[[Arizona Republic]] |first1=Yvonne |last1=Wingett Sanchez |first2=Ronald J |last2=Hansen |date=June 25, 2019 |accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Grisham also worked for [[Mitt Romney]]'s [[Mitt Romney 2012 presidential campaign|2012 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"fox10phoenix\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fox10phoenix.com/news/arizona-news/single-mother-from-the-valley-working-for-the-trump-white-house |title=Single mother from the Valley working for the Trump White House |first=Kari |last=Lake |date=June 25, 2017 |publisher=[[KSAZ-TV]] |website=fox10phoenix.com |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/>\n\nAfter Republican [[Mark Brnovich]] defeated Horne in the 2014 GOP primary, Grisham worked as a spokesperson for the [[Arizona House of Representatives]] Republican caucus.<ref name=azr_20190626 /> She revoked the [[Arizona Capitol Times]]'s press credentials hours after their reporting that the House speaker, [[David Gowan]], had traveled at state taxpayers' expense during his campaign for Congress.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=azct_20160408_Small>{{cite web |url=https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2016/04/08/this-new-background-check-policy-is-only-the-latest-retaliation-from-gowans-house/ |title=This new background check policy is only the latest retaliation from Gowan's House |first=Jim |last=Small |date=April 8, 2016 |newspaper=Arizona Capitol Times |accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref> Reporters refused to comply, and Gowan rescinded the order.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" />\n\nIn September 2015, Grisham worked as a press coordinator for [[Pope Francis's 2015 visit to North America#26 September (New York City, Philadelphia)|Pope Francis's visit to Philadelphia]] as an independent contractor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/politics/politicalinsider/2015/09/25/arizona-house-spokeswoman-prepping-pope/72826188/ |title=Arizona House spokeswoman prepping for the pope |first=Mary Jo |last=Pitzl |date=September 26, 2015 |work=The Republic |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Trump campaign and transition===\nCirca August 2015, Grisham started working as a press aide to [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Donald Trump 2016 presidential campaign|2016 presidential campaign]].<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/><ref name=\"azr_20170119\"/> She helped arrange his campaign stops in Phoenix and around the state and region throughout the primary, a role that quickly expanded to include his rallies around the U.S.<ref name=\"azr_20170119\"/> Grisham was on state payroll until May 2016, when she took an unpaid leave from the Arizona House of Representatives to work on Trump's campaign.<ref name=azct_20190625_Howard /><ref name=\"knau_20161201\">{{cite web|url=http://www.knau.org/post/trump-names-house-pr-person-staff-treasurer-adviser |title=Trump Names House PR Person To Staff, Treasurer As Adviser |date=December 1, 2016  |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[KNAU]] |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter his victory, Grisham was named a special adviser for operations and served on Trump's transition team.<ref name=\"azr_20170119\"/><ref name=\"knau_20161201\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1047287/sb/ALL/3|title=Schedule B for ALL Line|website=docquery.fec.gov |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1135946/sb/23/3|title=Schedule B for Line|website=docquery.fec.gov|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/forms/C00580100/1148952/sb/ALL/5|title=Schedule B for ALL Line|website=docquery.fec.gov |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> Arizona House speaker David Gowan paid her $19,000 in state salary over an 8-week period while she was serving as a member of the Trump transition team.<ref name=azct_20190625_Howard /><ref name=azct_20170425_Stephenson>{{cite web |url=https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/2017/04/25/tradition-dictates-no-show-no-problem-in-house-transition/ |title=FLOTUS spokeswoman Stephanie Grisham on state payroll while on Trump's victory tour and transition team |first=Hank |last=Stephenson |date=April 25, 2017 |newspaper=Arizona Capitol Times |accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Trump administration===\nAfter Trump's January 2017 inauguration, Grisham was named deputy press secretary for [[Sean Spicer]] in the West Wing of the White House.<ref name=\"fox10phoenix\"/><ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/>\n\nIn March 2017, First Lady Melania Trump moved her over to the East Wing.<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\"/><ref name=sentinel_20170327 /> A former White House colleague said that the president regretted losing Grisham to the first lady's office because of Grisham's loyalty and skill at handling the press while acting as his traveling press secretary. During that time, she built relationships with many reporters at events. Despite losing Grisham as part of his own staff, President Trump said he was satisfied that the first lady would \"be in good hands\". Grisham was described by several sources who had worked with her previously as being \"highly competent\" and \"self-aware\"; some suggested that she enjoyed \"trolling the press.\" <ref name=\"Beast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-white-house-wont-stop-melania-from-contradicting-trump|title=The White House Won't Stop Melania From Contradicting Trump|work=[[The Daily Beast]]|last=Markay|first=Lachlan|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=November 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Office of Special Counsel]] stated that Grisham violated the [[Hatch Act of 1939]] following a complaint by Senator [[Tom Carper]]. Grisham was accused of using her official [[Twitter]] account on July 11, 2018, to tweet out Trump's campaign slogan. Violation of the act is not a crime, but a workplace guideline, and the agency responded by sending Grisham a warning letter.<ref name=\"Hatch\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/melania-trump-spokesperson-violate-hatch-act-1132130|title=Melania Trump's Spokeswoman Stephanie Grisham Violated Hatch Act With 'Make America Great Again' Tweet|last=Hutzler|first=Alexandra|work=[[Newsweek]] |date=October 9, 2018|accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Grisham replaced [[Sarah Sanders]] as [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]] and [[White House Communications Director|White House communications director]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-grisham-idUSKCN1TQ29I|title=Longtime Trump aide Stephanie Grisham will succeed Sanders as press secretary |first=Steve |last=Holland |date=June 25, 2019 |agency=Reuters |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> Grisham's appointment was announced by Melania Trump via [[Twitter]] on June 25, 2019.<ref name=\"Fortune06142019\" /><ref name=cnn_20190625>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/25/politics/stephanie-grisham-press-secretary/index.html?no-st=1568740491|title=Trump taps Melania Trump's spokeswoman as next White House press secretary|publisher=CNN|last=Bennett|first=Kate|date=June 25, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref> The June 28, 2019 ''Annual Report to Congress on White House Office Personnel'' listed Grisham as \"Assistant to the President and Deputy Chief of Staff for Communications for the First Lady\", with an annual salary of $183,000.00.<ref name=ReportWHpersonnel_20190629>{{cite web |title=Annual Report to Congress on White House Personnel |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/July-1-2019-Report-FINAL.pdf |website=whitehouse.gov |publisher=Executive Office of the President |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830034415/https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/July-1-2019-Report-FINAL.pdf |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |date=June 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn September 5, 2019, the ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' published an opinion piece written by Grisham and her deputy [[Hogan Gidley]] entitled, \"The ''Washington Post''{{'}}s lost summer.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/op-eds/the-washington-posts-lost-summer|title=The Washington Post's lost summer |first1=Stephanie |last1=Grisham |first2=Hogan |last2=Gidley |date=September 5, 2019 |website=[[Washington Examiner]] |accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref> The authors asserted the ''Post'' had not reported on several Trump accomplishments that the paper actually did report. In one instance, the piece linked to a ''Post'' story entitled \"Trump becomes first sitting president to set foot into North Korea\" as the authors asserted the paper had not reported the event.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mediaite.com/trump/white-house-press-secretaries-publish-op-ed-claiming-washington-post-didnt-cover-stories-the-paper-actually-did-cover/|title=Stephanie Grisham Claims ''Washington Post'' Didn't Cover Stories the Paper Actually Did Cover |first=Connor |last=Mannion |date=September 6, 2019 |work=[[Mediaite]] |accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2019, when asked by the hosts of Fox & Friends if the White House planned to resume its daily press briefing Grisham said \"not right now... I mean, ultimately, if the president decides that it's something we should do, we can do that, but right now he's doing just fine. And to be honest, the briefings have become a lot of theater. And I think that a lot of reporters were doing it to get famous. I mean, yeah, they're writing books now. I mean, they're all getting famous off of this presidency. And so, I think it's great what we're doing now.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2mymMUR|title=White House press secretary says daily briefings aren't coming back any time soon|last=Forgey|first=Quint|date=September 23, 2019 |website=[[POLITICO]] |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2019, appearing on Fox & Friends, Grisham defended Trump's description of \"Never Trump Republicans\" as \"Human scum\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1187063301731209220?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed&ref_url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/press-secretary-stephanie-grisham-trump-human-scum|title=The Never Trumper Republicans, though on respirators with not many left, are in certain ways worse and more dangerous for our Country than the Do Nothing Democrats. Watch out for them, they are human scum!|last=Trump|first=Donald J.|date=October 23, 2019|website=@realDonaldTrump|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>  When asked if Trump should apologize, Grisham said \"No, no, he shouldn't. The people who are against him and who have been against him and working against his [agenda] since the day they took office are just that. It is horrible that people are working against a president who is delivering results for this country and has been since day one. And, the fact that people continue to try to negate anything he's been trying to do and take away from the good work he's doing on behalf of the American people, they deserve strong language like that.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/press-secretary-stephanie-grisham-trump-human-scum|title=Press secretary Grisham on Trump's 'human scum' tweet: Those working against him are 'just that'|last=Musto|first=Julia|date=October 24, 2019|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, 2019, in response to criticism of President Trump by his former chief of staff Gen. [[John F. Kelly]] (Ret.) Grisham stated: \"I worked with John Kelly, and he was totally unequipped to handle the genius of our President.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/26/john-kelly-trump-impeachment-yes-man-058450|title=White House hits back at John Kelly over impeachment remarks|last=Semones|first=Evan |date=October 26, 2019 |website=POLITICO |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2019, during the testimony of [[William B. Taylor Jr.]], Grisham commented that the [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump]] was a \"sham hearing\" that is \"not only boring, it is a colossal waste of taxpayer time & money.\"<ref name=RollCall_20191113>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/whitehouse/white-house-claims-trump-too-busy-to-watch-boring-impeachment-hearing |title=White House says Trump 'too busy' to watch 'boring' impeachment hearing |first=John T |last=Bennett |date=November 13, 2019 |newspaper=[[Roll Call]] |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=nytimes_20191113>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/13/us/politics/trump-impeachment.html |title=Full Video and Analysis of Day 1 of Impeachment Hearing Testimony |date=November 13, 2019 |website=New York Times |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=RollCall_20191113 />\n\nThat same month, Grisham claimed that Obama administration officials had left \"you will fail\" notes for the incoming Trump administration officials. Numerous Obama administration officials rejected the claim. Grisham ultimately retracted her assertion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/nov/20/stephanie-grisham-obama-officials-you-will-fail-notes-claim|title=Trump press secretary backtracks claim Obama officials left 'You will fail' notes|last=Gabbatt|first=Adam|date=November 20, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 22, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, Grisham defended President Trump's implication that former congressman [[John Dingell]] was in hell. She described Trump as a \"counter-puncher\" who was \"under attack.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-press-secretary-president-trump-suggested-late/story?id=67821688|title=White House defends Trump as 'counter-puncher' after he suggests late Michigan congressman in hell|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/19/white-house-defends-trumps-attack-on-dead-lawmaker-john-dingell/ |title=White House defends Trump's attack on dead lawmaker John Dingell |first=Bob |last=Fredericks |date=December 19, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |access-date=January 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn April 7, 2020, it was announced that Grisham left her role as White House Press Secretary and returned to the East Wing to serve as Melania Trump's chief of staff,<ref name=\"CNN-Out\" /> effective that same day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Zilbermints |first=Regina |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/491525-grisham-leaves-role-as-white-house-press-secretary |title=Grisham leaves role as White House press secretary |date=April 7, 2020 |work=The Hill |access-date=April 7, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Briefing controversy===\nAs of March 11, 2020, Grisham had not conducted a formal press briefing in 365 days.<ref name=cnn_20200311>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/white-house-press-briefing-one-year/index.html |title=Make sure to remember this appalling 1-year anniversary |first=Chris |last=Cillizza |date=March 11, 2020 |work=The Point with Chris Cillizza |publisher=CNN |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=nyt_20200110>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/10/business/media/stephanie-grisham-trump-press-secretary.html |title=Stephanie Grisham: Trump's Press Secretary Who Doesn't Meet the Press |date=January 10, 2020 |first1=Michael M. |last1=Grynbaum |first2=Katie |last2=Rogers |newspaper=New York Times |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> However, she appeared on Fox News, Fox Business Network, [[One America News Network]], and the Sinclair Broadcast Group many times during the same period.<ref name=wapo_20200111 /><ref name=nyt_20200110 /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/11/media/stephanie-grisham-briefings-fox/index.html|title=White House press secretary Stephanie Grisham has yet to hold a briefing with reporters, but finds time for Fox News |date=November 11, 2019 |first=Oliver |last=Darcy |publisher=CNN |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Anderson Cooper 360\u00b0]]'' devoted two prime-time segments in one week to question whether taxpayers should pay her $183,000 salary,<ref name=nyt_20200110 /> and her hypocrisy.<ref name=cnn_20200110>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/01/10/stephanie-grisham-again-ridiculist-sot-ac360-vpx.cnn/video/playlists/ac360-videos/ |title=Cooper to WH press sec.: Your secret is safe with us |first=Anderson |last=Cooper |date=January 10, 2020 |work=The Ridiculist |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> \"Miss Grisham has gone from 'we are human beings' to 'they are human scum.' ... It's actually really kind of sad....\"<ref name=cnn_20200107>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/01/07/stephanie-grisham-press-briefings-ridiculist-sot-pkg-ac360-vpx.cnn/video/playlists/ac360-videos/ |title=Cooper calls out White House over lack of press briefings |first=Anderson |last=Cooper |date=January 7, 2020 |work=The Ridiculist |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anderson-cooper-stephanie-grisham-hypocrisy_n_5e143513c5b6b5a713bfeef9 |title=Anderson Cooper Nails Hypocrisy Of Trump Press Secretary Stephanie Grisham |first=Lee |last=Moran |date=January 7, 2020 |website=[[HuffPost]] |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/anderson-cooper-stephanie-grisham-cnn-responds-white-house-press-secretary-2020-1 |title=Anderson Cooper doubled down in his feud with White House press secretary Stephanie Grisham, calling her statements 'kind of sad' |first=Kat |last=Tenbarge |date=January 7, 2020 |website=Business Insider |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Her \"unintentionally ironic and deeply hypocritical\" social media statements and infrequent televised interviews \"appear meant to defend the president but actually point out the president's own failings.\"<ref name=cnn_20200110 /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anderson-cooper-stephanie-grisham-subverting-trump_n_5e182730c5b650c621dc40ca |title=Anderson Cooper Has A Theory About Stephanie Grisham Secretly Working Against Trump |first=Lee |last=Moran |date=January 10, 2020 |website=[[HuffPost]] |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>  Margaret Sullivan has commented in the ''[[Washington Post]]'' that Grisham \"may hold the title but she's not doing the job\".<ref name=wapo_20200111>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/stephanie-grisham-is-not-the-worst-ever-white-house-press-secretary-heres-why/2020/01/10/405340bc-33be-11ea-a053-dc6d944ba776_story.html |title=Stephanie Grisham is not the worst-ever White House press secretary. Here's why. |first=Margaret |last=Sullivan |date=January 11, 2020 |newspaper=Washington Post |access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAuthors [[Don Winslow]] and [[Stephen King]] pledged to donate $100,000 each to charity after Grisham held a 60-minute briefing answering questions from the White House press corps.<ref name=wapo_20200111 /><ref name=nyt_20200110 /> Also, 13 former White House and military press secretaries from three administrations before Trump published a letter calling for the restoration of press briefings.<ref name=wapo_20200111 /><ref name=nyt_20200110 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/10/opinions/ex-press-secretaries-open-letter-on-press-briefings/index.html |title=Why America needs to hear from its government |date=January 10, 2020 |publisher=CNN |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> The press briefings never occurred.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Gearan |first=Anne |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/stephanie-grisham-out-as-white-house-press-secretary-after-eight-months-during-which-she-held-no-regular-news-briefings/2020/04/07/6d93b7aa-75bd-11ea-87da-77a8136c1a6d_story.html |title=Stephanie Grisham out as White House press secretary after eight months during which she held no regular news briefings |date=April 7, 2020 |work=Washington Post |access-date=April 12, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=HouseEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollow |first2=closeAnne GearanWhite House reporterEmailEmailBioBioFollowFollowJosh Dawsey closeJosh DawseyReporter covering the White |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Incidents of driving while intoxicated==\nOn January 9, 2013, Grisham was pulled over for speeding in [[Gilbert, Arizona|Gilbert]], [[Maricopa County, Arizona]]. The officer observed Grisham's signs of intoxication, and she failed a field sobriety test. Grisham denied consuming any alcohol, but said she had taken a [[Xanax]] 90 minutes earlier and a [[Zoloft]] the prior night. A blood test revealed Grisham's blood alcohol content to be .105 percent, which is above the .08 legal limit in Arizona. She also was found to be driving on a suspended license since August 2012 for failure to answer a traffic citation. In August 2014, Grisham accepted a plea bargain agreement that reduced the charge to misdemeanor reckless driving, plus two years of probation.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190625\" /><ref name=\"tsg_20190828\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesmokinggun.com/buster/arizona/press-secretary-collars-162053|title=Like So Many Of His Associates, Donald Trump's New Press Secretary Has Posed For Some Mug Shots|date=August 28, 2019|website=The Smoking Gun|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> She returned to court twice for failure to pay the $779 in fines and failure to complete a [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] program.<ref name=azr_20190626 />\n\nShortly after midnight, December 5, 2015, Grisham was arrested again in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], [[Maricopa County, Arizona]] for driving without her headlights and suspicion of [[driving under the influence]]; thus violating her probation.<ref name=azr_20190626 /> Grisham failed to appear at her court hearing on January 19, 2016,<ref name=azr_20190626 /> whereupon the judge issued a warrant for her arrest.<ref name=\"tsg_20190828\" /> Afterwards, Grisham pleaded guilty.  In July 2016, she was ordered into a treatment program and to pay nearly $1,600 in court costs and fines.<ref name=azr_20190626 /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190625\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes_20190822\" /><ref name=\"tsg_20190828\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of the Donald Trump presidency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tucsonsentinel.com/tag/stephanie+grisham/ Stephanie Grisham] at ''[[TucsonSentinel.com]]''\n* [https://azcapitoltimes.com/news/tag/stephanie-grisham/ Stephanie Grisham] at the ''[[Arizona Capitol Times]]''\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/meet-melania-trumps-enforcer-its-not-her-husband/2018/12/07/52a5a864-f8c7-11e8-863c-9e2f864d47e7_story.html/ Stephanie Grisham] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bill Shine]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Communications Director|White House Director of Communications]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sarah Sanders]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Press Secretary]]|years=2019\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kayleigh McEnany]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WHCD}}\n{{WHPS}}\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grisham, Stephanie}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:American press secretaries]]\n[[Category:Arizona Republicans]]\n[[Category:Colorado Republicans]]\n[[Category:Colorado Mesa University alumni]]\n[[Category:First Lady of the United States press secretaries]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:White House Communications Directors]]\n[[Category:White House Press Secretaries]]\n", "name_user": "Javert2113", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing style/layout errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephanie_Grisham"}
{"title_page": "Francesco Di Carlo", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian mobster}}\n'''Francesco Di Carlo''' (February 18, 1941&nbsp;\u2013 April 16, 2020)<ref name=\"death\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.tp24.it/2020/04/16/antimafia/coronavirus-morto-parigi-pentito-francesco-carlo/148149%20Coronavirus,%20morto%20a%20Parigi%20il%20pentito%20Francesco%20Di%20Carlo |title=Coronavirus, morto a Parigi il pentito Francesco Di Carlo |last=Tp24.it |date=2020-04-16 |website=TP24.it |language=it |access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> was a member of the [[Sicilian Mafia]] who turned state witness ([[pentito]]&nbsp;\u2014 a mafioso turned informer) in 1996. He was accused of being the killer of [[Roberto Calvi]], nicknamed \"God's banker\", because he was in charge of [[Banco Ambrosiano]] and his close association with the [[Institute for the Works of Religion|Vatican Bank]]. He died after contracting [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|pandemic]] on April 16, 2020.<ref name=\"death\" />\n\n==Early career==\nDi Carlo was born in [[Altofonte]], where he was initiated into the Mafia family in 1966 by the boss at the time, Salvatore La Barbera (not to be confused with the [[Salvatore La Barbera|Palermo Centro boss]] who was killed in 1963).<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.narcomafie.it/sentenza_dellutri.pdf Sentenza nei confronti di Dell\u2019Utri Marcello e Cin\u00e0 Gaetano] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928051033/http://www.narcomafie.it/sentenza_dellutri.pdf |date=2007-09-28 }} December 11, 2004</ref> He became ''capo famiglia'' in the mid 1970s. Altofonte was part of the [[mandamento (Sicilian Mafia)|mandamento]] of [[San Giuseppe Jato]], headed by [[Antonio Salamone]] and [[Giovanni Brusca|Bernardo Brusca]]. According to the [[pentito]] [[Giuseppe Marchese]], Di Carlo was an influential mafioso and a very competent drug trafficker connected with the [[Corleonesi Mafia clan]].\n\nDi Carlo was described as an elegant and intelligent mafioso who received an education at the prestigious [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] college of [[Jesuit College of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] in [[Palermo]] where he met the prince [[Alessandro Vanni Calvello]], who would be best man at his marriage. Di Carlo and Vanni Calvello were partners in the nightclub \"Il Castello\" in [[San Nicola Arena]], just outside Palermo on the highway to [[Messina]]. The club was popular with the ''beau monde'' of Palermo, and hosted concerts by such visiting stars as [[Ray Charles]] and [[Amanda Lear]]. However, during the daylight hourd the Mafia used it as a meeting place.\n\n==Expelled from Cosa Nostra==\nDi Carlo was expelled (''posato'') from Cosa Nostra, because of a conflict about a lost shipment of heroin or an unpaid consignment of [[hashish]]. Because of his useful contributions for the Mafia he was not killed, but had to leave Italy. He moved to [[London]]. His brother [[Andrea Di Carlo]] took over the command of the Mafia family and became a member of the [[Sicilian Mafia Commission]].\n\nAccording to Di Carlo he was expelled in 1982 because he refused to betray some members of the [[Cuntrera-Caruana Mafia clan]] ([[Pasquale Cuntrera]] and [[Alfonso Caruana]]), during the Mafia war in the [[province of Agrigento]] that ran parallel to the [[Second Mafia War]] in [[Palermo]]. Mafia boss [[Carmelo Colletti]], connected with the Corleonesi, had taken over the command after killing [[Giuseppe Settecasi]] and his lieutenant [[Leonardo Caruana]]. He wanted the other Cuntreras and Caruanas out of the way as well. However, it was Colletti who was killed in 1983.\n\n==Drug trafficking==\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] Di Carlo was involved in hashish and heroin trafficking. He bought a mansion in [[Woking]], Surrey, in the stockbrokers-belt near London. In the United Kingdom he teamed up with [[Alfonso Caruana]]. Di Carlo created an infrastructure to facilitate the smuggling operations: he owned a hotel, travel agencies and import-export companies.<ref>''[http://www.tni.org/archives/tblick/aruba.htm The Rothschilds of the Mafia on Aruba]'', by Tom Blickman, Transnational Organized Crime, Vol. 3, No. 2, Summer 1997.</ref>\n\nIn June 1985 British Custom & Excise and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) seized 60 kilograms of heroin in a controlled delivery. In the United Kingdom, Di Carlo was arrested with three others. In March 1987 Di Carlo was convicted and sentenced to a 25-year prison term for heroin trafficking.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE5DC103DF931A25750C0A961948260 ''Britain Sentences 4 in Mafia''], The New York Times, March 12, 1987</ref>\n\n==Pentito==\nIn June 1996 Di Carlo decided to collaborate with the Italian authorities. He was transferred from his United Kingdom prison to Rome. He was hailed as the \"new [[Tommaso Buscetta|Buscetta]]\". Di Carlo mentioned several politicians to be members of Cosa Nostra, among others: the [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democrat]] politician [[Bernardo Mattarella]], the former president of Sicily [[Giovanni Provenzano]], and Giovanni Musotto, father of [[Francesco Musotto]], former president of the [[Province of Palermo]] who has been accused of Mafia association.<ref name=rep111096>{{in lang|it}} [http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1996/10/11/vi-dico-nomi-dei-padri-della.html 'Vi dico i nomi dei padri della mafia'], La Repubblica, October 11, 1996</ref>\n\nHe also testified about the murder of journalist [[Mauro De Mauro]]. The investigative reporter had been kidnapped and killed by the Mafia in 1970. Di Carlo testified in 2001 that De Mauro was killed, because he had learned that one of his former fascist friends, Prince [[Junio Valerio Borghese]], was planning a coup d'\u00e9tat (the so-called [[Golpe Borghese]]) with like-minded army officers determined to stop what they considered as Italy's drift to the left.<ref name=rep260101>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/online/cronaca/mdemauro/mdemauro/mdemauro.html \"De Mauro venne ucciso perch\u00e9 sapeva del golpe\"], La Repubblica, January 26, 2001</ref><ref name=ind190605>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/revealed-how-story-of-mafia-plot-to-launch-coup-cost-reporter-his-life-494619.html Revealed: how story of Mafia plot to launch coup cost reporter his life], The Independent on Sunday, June 19, 2005</ref><ref name=rep180605>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/2005/f/sezioni/cronaca/demauromafia/demauromafia/demauromafia.html De Mauro ucciso per uno scoop: scopr\u00ec il patto tra boss e golpisti], La Repubblica, June 18, 2005</ref>  Di Carlo became an important witness in numerous antimafia trials and also testified in the trials against former Prime Minister [[Giulio Andreotti]] and [[Silvio Berlusconi]]\u2019s right hand man [[Marcello Dell'Utri]].\n\nHe wanted to move to Canada as part of an international agreement that allows him to be relocated almost anywhere in the world. In an exclusive interview with [[W-FIVE]], Di Carlo confirmed the allegation that the Sicilian Mafia considers Canada to be the best place in the world to conduct their criminal businesses. In November 2000, Di Carlo spoke to W-FIVE in hopes of sending a message to [[Alfonso Caruana]]. During his interview he revealed that the high council of the Mafia had ordered Di Carlo to murder Caruana, who had fallen out of favour. Di Carlo refused, saving Alfonso's life, but putting his own in danger. Di Carlo wanted the Caruanas to remember this life-saving favour.<ref name=wfive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090414054350/https://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1025827381647_21236581/ The Canadian connection], W-FIVE, November 7, 2000</ref>\n\n==Involvement in Roberto Calvi murder==\nIn July 1991 the pentito [[Francesco Marino Mannoia]] claimed that Di Carlo had killed [[Roberto Calvi]], nicknamed \"God's banker\", because he was in charge of [[Banco Ambrosiano]], in which the Vatican Bank was the main share-holder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061015113807/http://www.americanatheist.org/pope99/calvi.html|title=THROUGH THE LOOKING GLASS Vatican Politics, the Calvi Murder and Beyond...|date=October 15, 2006|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> Calvi had been killed because he had lost Mafia funds when Banco Ambrosiano collapsed. The order to kill Calvi had come from Mafia boss [[Giuseppe Cal\u00f2]].\n\nWhen Di Carlo became state witness in June 1996, he denied that he was the killer, but admitted that he had been approached by Cal\u00f2 to do the job. However, Di Carlo could not be reached in time, and when he later called Cal\u00f2, the latter said that everything had been taken care of already. According to Di Carlo, the killers were [[Vincenzo Casillo]] and [[Sergio Vaccari]], who belonged to the [[Camorra]] from Naples and have been killed since.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/core/Content/displayPrintable.jhtml?xml=/news/2005/12/11/wmafia11.xml&site=5&page=0 Mafia wanted me to kill Calvi, says jailed gangster], Daily Telegraph, December 10, 2005</ref><ref name=sm120512>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/mafia-hitman-reveals-he-was-hired-to-kill-830122 Mafia hitman reveals he was hired to kill God's banker Roberto Calvi ], The Sunday Mirror, May 12, 2012</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{in lang|fr}} Calvi, Fabrizio (1993). ''L'Europe des parrains. La Mafia \u00e0 l'assaut de l'Europe'', Paris: Grasset {{ISBN|2-246-46061-1}}\n*{{in lang|it}} Caruso, Alfio (2000). ''[http://www.alfiocaruso.com/da_cosa_cap.htm Da cosa nasce cosa. Storia della mafia del 1943 a oggi]'', Milan: Longanesi {{ISBN|88-304-1620-7}}\n\n{{Sicilian Mafia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Carlo, Francesco}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Altofonte]]\n[[Category:Sicilian Mafiosi]]\n[[Category:Pentiti]]\n[[Category:Italian drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian mobster}}\n'''Francesco Di Carlo''' (February 18, 1941&nbsp;\u2013 April 16, 2020)<ref name=\"death\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.tp24.it/2020/04/16/antimafia/coronavirus-morto-parigi-pentito-francesco-carlo/148149%20Coronavirus,%20morto%20a%20Parigi%20il%20pentito%20Francesco%20Di%20Carlo |title=Coronavirus, morto a Parigi il pentito Francesco Di Carlo |last=Tp24.it |date=2020-04-16 |website=TP24.it |language=it |access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> was a member of the [[Sicilian Mafia]] who turned state witness ([[pentito]]&nbsp;\u2014 a mafioso turned informer) in 1996. He was accused of being the killer of [[Roberto Calvi]], nicknamed \"God's banker\", because he was in charge of [[Banco Ambrosiano]] and his close association with the [[Institute for the Works of Religion|Vatican Bank]]. He died after contracting [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|pandemic]] on April 16, 2020.<ref name=\"death\" />\n\n==Early career==\nDi Carlo was born in [[Altofonte]], where he was initiated into the Mafia family in 1966 by the boss at the time, Salvatore La Barbera (not to be confused with the [[Salvatore La Barbera|Palermo Centro boss]] who was killed in 1963).<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.narcomafie.it/sentenza_dellutri.pdf Sentenza nei confronti di Dell\u2019Utri Marcello e Cin\u00e0 Gaetano] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928051033/http://www.narcomafie.it/sentenza_dellutri.pdf |date=2007-09-28 }} December 11, 2004</ref> He became ''capo famiglia'' in the mid 1970s. Altofonte was part of the [[mandamento (Sicilian Mafia)|mandamento]] of [[San Giuseppe Jato]], headed by [[Antonio Salamone]] and [[Giovanni Brusca|Bernardo Brusca]]. According to the [[pentito]] [[Giuseppe Marchese]], Di Carlo was an influential mafioso and a very competent drug trafficker connected with the [[Corleonesi Mafia clan]].\n\nDi Carlo was described as an elegant and intelligent mafioso who received an education at the prestigious [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] college of [[Jesuit College of Gonzaga|Gonzaga]] in [[Palermo]] where he met the prince [[Alessandro Vanni Calvello]], who would be best man at his marriage. Di Carlo and Vanni Calvello were partners in the nightclub \"Il Castello\" in [[San Nicola Arena]], just outside Palermo on the highway to [[Messina]]. The club was popular with the ''beau monde'' of Palermo, and hosted concerts by such visting stars as [[Ray Charles]] and [[Amanda Lear]]. However, during the daylight hourd the Mafia used it as a meeting place.\n\n==Expelled from Cosa Nostra==\nDi Carlo was expelled (''posato'') from Cosa Nostra, because of a conflict about a lost shipment of heroin or an unpaid consignment of [[hashish]]. Because of his useful contributions for the Mafia he was not killed, but had to leave Italy. He moved to [[London]]. His brother [[Andrea Di Carlo]] took over the command of the Mafia family and became a member of the [[Sicilian Mafia Commission]].\n\nAccording to Di Carlo he was expelled in 1982 because he refused to betray some members of the [[Cuntrera-Caruana Mafia clan]] ([[Pasquale Cuntrera]] and [[Alfonso Caruana]]), during the Mafia war in the [[province of Agrigento]] that ran parallel to the [[Second Mafia War]] in [[Palermo]]. Mafia boss [[Carmelo Colletti]], connected with the Corleonesi, had taken over the command after killing [[Giuseppe Settecasi]] and his lieutenant [[Leonardo Caruana]]. He wanted the other Cuntreras and Caruanas out of the way as well. However, it was Colletti who was killed in 1983.\n\n==Drug trafficking==\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] Di Carlo was involved in hashish and heroin trafficking. He bought a mansion in [[Woking]], Surrey, in the stockbrokers-belt near London. In the United Kingdom he teamed up with [[Alfonso Caruana]]. Di Carlo created an infrastructure to facilitate the smuggling operations: he owned a hotel, travel agencies and import-export companies.<ref>''[http://www.tni.org/archives/tblick/aruba.htm The Rothschilds of the Mafia on Aruba]'', by Tom Blickman, Transnational Organized Crime, Vol. 3, No. 2, Summer 1997.</ref>\n\nIn June 1985 British Custom & Excise and the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) seized 60 kilograms of heroin in a controlled delivery. In the United Kingdom, Di Carlo was arrested with three others. In March 1987 Di Carlo was convicted and sentenced to a 25-year prison term for heroin trafficking.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE5DC103DF931A25750C0A961948260 ''Britain Sentences 4 in Mafia''], The New York Times, March 12, 1987</ref>\n\n==Pentito==\nIn June 1996 Di Carlo decided to collaborate with the Italian authorities. He was transferred from his United Kingdom prison to Rome. He was hailed as the \"new [[Tommaso Buscetta|Buscetta]]\". Di Carlo mentioned several politicians to be members of Cosa Nostra, among others: the [[Christian Democracy (Italy)|Christian Democrat]] politician [[Bernardo Mattarella]], the former president of Sicily [[Giovanni Provenzano]], and Giovanni Musotto, father of [[Francesco Musotto]], former president of the [[Province of Palermo]] who has been accused of Mafia association.<ref name=rep111096>{{in lang|it}} [http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1996/10/11/vi-dico-nomi-dei-padri-della.html 'Vi dico i nomi dei padri della mafia'], La Repubblica, October 11, 1996</ref>\n\nHe also testified about the murder of journalist [[Mauro De Mauro]]. The investigative reporter had been kidnapped and killed by the Mafia in 1970. Di Carlo testified in 2001 that De Mauro was killed, because he had learned that one of his former fascist friends, Prince [[Junio Valerio Borghese]], was planning a coup d'\u00e9tat (the so-called [[Golpe Borghese]]) with like-minded army officers determined to stop what they considered as Italy's drift to the left.<ref name=rep260101>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/online/cronaca/mdemauro/mdemauro/mdemauro.html \"De Mauro venne ucciso perch\u00e9 sapeva del golpe\"], La Repubblica, January 26, 2001</ref><ref name=ind190605>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/revealed-how-story-of-mafia-plot-to-launch-coup-cost-reporter-his-life-494619.html Revealed: how story of Mafia plot to launch coup cost reporter his life], The Independent on Sunday, June 19, 2005</ref><ref name=rep180605>{{in lang|it}} [http://www.repubblica.it/2005/f/sezioni/cronaca/demauromafia/demauromafia/demauromafia.html De Mauro ucciso per uno scoop: scopr\u00ec il patto tra boss e golpisti], La Repubblica, June 18, 2005</ref>  Di Carlo became an important witness in numerous antimafia trials and also testified in the trials against former Prime Minister [[Giulio Andreotti]] and [[Silvio Berlusconi]]\u2019s right hand man [[Marcello Dell'Utri]].\n\nHe wanted to move to Canada as part of an international agreement that allows him to be relocated almost anywhere in the world. In an exclusive interview with [[W-FIVE]], Di Carlo confirmed the allegation that the Sicilian Mafia considers Canada to be the best place in the world to conduct their criminal businesses. In November 2000, Di Carlo spoke to W-FIVE in hopes of sending a message to [[Alfonso Caruana]]. During his interview he revealed that the high council of the Mafia had ordered Di Carlo to murder Caruana, who had fallen out of favour. Di Carlo refused, saving Alfonso's life, but putting his own in danger. Di Carlo wanted the Caruanas to remember this life-saving favour.<ref name=wfive>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090414054350/https://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/1025827381647_21236581/ The Canadian connection], W-FIVE, November 7, 2000</ref>\n\n==Involvement in Roberto Calvi murder==\nIn July 1991 the pentito [[Francesco Marino Mannoia]] claimed that Di Carlo had killed [[Roberto Calvi]], nicknamed \"God's banker\", because he was in charge of [[Banco Ambrosiano]], in which the Vatican Bank was the main share-holder.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061015113807/http://www.americanatheist.org/pope99/calvi.html|title=THROUGH THE LOOKING GLASS Vatican Politics, the Calvi Murder and Beyond...|date=October 15, 2006|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> Calvi had been killed because he had lost Mafia funds when Banco Ambrosiano collapsed. The order to kill Calvi had come from Mafia boss [[Giuseppe Cal\u00f2]].\n\nWhen Di Carlo became state witness in June 1996, he denied that he was the killer, but admitted that he had been approached by Cal\u00f2 to do the job. However, Di Carlo could not be reached in time, and when he later called Cal\u00f2, the latter said that everything had been taken care of already. According to Di Carlo, the killers were [[Vincenzo Casillo]] and [[Sergio Vaccari]], who belonged to the [[Camorra]] from Naples and have been killed since.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/core/Content/displayPrintable.jhtml?xml=/news/2005/12/11/wmafia11.xml&site=5&page=0 Mafia wanted me to kill Calvi, says jailed gangster], Daily Telegraph, December 10, 2005</ref><ref name=sm120512>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/mafia-hitman-reveals-he-was-hired-to-kill-830122 Mafia hitman reveals he was hired to kill God's banker Roberto Calvi ], The Sunday Mirror, May 12, 2012</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*{{in lang|fr}} Calvi, Fabrizio (1993). ''L'Europe des parrains. La Mafia \u00e0 l'assaut de l'Europe'', Paris: Grasset {{ISBN|2-246-46061-1}}\n*{{in lang|it}} Caruso, Alfio (2000). ''[http://www.alfiocaruso.com/da_cosa_cap.htm Da cosa nasce cosa. Storia della mafia del 1943 a oggi]'', Milan: Longanesi {{ISBN|88-304-1620-7}}\n\n{{Sicilian Mafia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Di Carlo, Francesco}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Altofonte]]\n[[Category:Sicilian Mafiosi]]\n[[Category:Pentiti]]\n[[Category:Italian drug traffickers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in France]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: visting->visiting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francesco_Di_Carlo"}
{"title_page": "Bonus Army", "text_new": "{{short description|1930s US veterans protest movement}}\n{{use mdy dates |date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict = Bonus Army Conflict\n|image = Bonus marchers 05510 2004 001 a.gif\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption = Bonus Army marchers (left) confront the police.\n|date = In time of Jesus \n|place = [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States]]\n|casus = Impoverishment of WWI veterans from the Depression\n|result = Bonus Army dispersed, demands rejected, Herbert Hoover loses [[1932 United States presidential election|1932 Presidential election]] \n|combatant1 = Bonus Army\n|combatant2 = {{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]\n|commander1 = Walter W. Waters\n|commander2 = [[Herbert Hoover]]<br />[[Douglas MacArthur]]<br />[[George S. Patton]]\n|strength1 = 17,000 veterans<br />26,000 others\n|strength2 = 500 infantry<br />500 cavalry<br />6 [[M1917 light tank]]s<br />800 policemen\n|casualties1 = First day 2 dead; 1,017 injured,{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} total unknown \n|casualties2 = At least 69 police injured\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Aftermath of World War I}}\n\nThe '''Bonus Army''' was a group of 43,000 [[demonstration (protest)|demonstrators]] \u2013 made up of 17,000 U.S. [[World War I]] veterans, together with their families and affiliated groups \u2013 who gathered in [[Washington, D.C.]] in mid-1932 to demand early cash redemption of their service certificates. Organizers called the demonstrators the \"Bonus Expeditionary Force\", to echo the name of World War I's [[American Expeditionary Forces]], while the media referred to them as the \"Bonus Army\" or \"Bonus Marchers\". The demonstrators were led by Walter W. Waters, a former sergeant.\n\nMany of the war veterans had been out of work since the beginning of the [[Great Depression]]. The [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act]] of 1924 had awarded them bonuses in the form of certificates they could not redeem until 1948. Each certificate, issued to a qualified veteran soldier, bore a face value equal to the soldier's promised payment with compound interest. The principal demand of the Bonus Army was the immediate cash payment of their certificates.\n\nOn July 28, [[U.S. Attorney General]] [[William D. Mitchell]] ordered the veterans removed from all government property. Washington police met with resistance, shot at the protestors, and two veterans were wounded and later died. President [[Herbert Hoover]] then ordered the U.S. Army to clear the marchers' campsite. Army Chief of Staff General [[Douglas MacArthur]] commanded a contingent of infantry and cavalry, supported by six tanks. The Bonus Army marchers with their wives and children were driven out, and their shelters and belongings burned. \n \nA second, smaller Bonus March in 1933 at the start of the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] administration was defused in May with an offer of jobs with the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] at [[Fort Hunt, Virginia]], which most of the group accepted. Those who chose not to work for the CCC by the May 22 deadline were given transportation home.<ref>\"'Take Job in the Forest or Go Home' Is Alternative Given to Bonus Boys\", ''Middlesboro (Kentucky) Daily News'', May 17, 1933, p1; \"Bonus Marchers Weaken; Accept Jobs in Ax Corps\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', May 20, 1933, p1</ref> In 1936, Congress overrode President Roosevelt's veto and paid the veterans their bonus nine years early.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Bonus army on Capitol lawn cph.3a00515.jpg|thumb|Members of the Bonus Army camped out on the lawn of the U.S. Capitol building]]\nThe practice of war-time military bonuses began in 1776, as payment for the difference between what a soldier earned and what he could have earned had he not enlisted. The practice derived from British legislation passed in the 1592\u201393 session of Parliament to provide medical care and maintenance for disabled veterans and bonuses for serving soldiers. Similar legislation for disabled veterans later only progressively passed by the North American colonies, beginning with Virginia in 1624.{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}}\n\nIn 1781, most of the [[Continental Army]] was [[Demobilization|demobilized]]. Two years later, hundreds of [[Pennsylvania]] war veterans [[Pennsylvania Mutiny of 1783|marched on Philadelphia]], then the nation's capital, surrounded the State House, where the [[U.S. Congress]] was in session, and demanded back pay. Congress fled to [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and several weeks later, the [[U.S. Army]] expelled the war veterans from Philadelphia.{{citation needed|date = February 2018\n\n\nIn August 1776, Congress adopted the first national pension law providing half pay for life for disabled veterans. Considerable pressure was applied to expand benefits to match the British system for serving soldiers and sailors but had little support from the colonial government until mass desertions at the [[Battle of Valley Forge]] that threatened the existence of the [[Continental Army]] led [[George Washington]] to become a strong advocate. Congress progressively passed legislation from 1788 covering pensions and bonuses, eventually extending eligibility to widows in 1836.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graves|first1=Will|title=Pension Acts An Overview of Revolutionary War Pension and Bounty Land Legislation and the Southern Campaigns Pension Transcription Project|url=http://revwarapps.org/revwar-pension-acts.htm|website=Southern Campaigns Revolutionary War Pension Statements & Rosters|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore World War I, the soldiers' military service bonus (adjusted for rank) was land and money; a Continental Army private received {{convert|100|acre|ha}} and $80.00 (2017: $1,968.51) at war's end, while a major general received {{convert|1100|acre|ha}}. In 1855, Congress increased the land-grant minimum to {{convert|160|acre|ha}}, and reduced the eligibility requirements to fourteen days of military service or one battle; moreover, the bonus also applied to veterans of any Indian war. The provision of land eventually became a major political issue, particularly in Tennessee where almost 40% of arable land had been given to veterans as part of their bonus. By 1860, {{convert|73500000|acre|ha}} had been issued and lack of available arable land led to the program's abandonment and replacement with a cash-only system.{{citation needed|date = July 2017}} Breaking with tradition, the veterans of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] did not receive a bonus and after [[World War I]], that became a political matter when they received only a $60 bonus. The [[American Legion]], created in 1919, led a political movement for an additional bonus.<ref name=greenberg/>\n\n[[File:USA-Cinderella-Stamp-1932 Pay the Bonus.jpg|thumb|left|[[Cinderella stamp]] (USA, 1932) supporting the Bonus Army]]\nOn May 15, 1924, President [[Calvin Coolidge]] vetoed a bill granting bonuses to veterans of World War I, saying: \"patriotism... bought and paid for is not patriotism.\" Congress overrode his veto a few days later,<ref name=greenberg>David Greenberg, ''Calvin Coolidge'' (NY: Henry Holt, 2006), 78\u20139</ref> enacting the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act]]. Each veteran was to receive a dollar for each day of domestic service, up to a maximum of $500 ({{Inflation|US|500|1924|r=-2|fmt=eq}}), and $1.25 for each day of overseas service, up to a maximum of $625 ({{Inflation|US|625|1924|r=-2|fmt=eq}}).{{Inflation/fn|US}} Amounts of $50 or less were immediately paid. All other amounts were issued as Certificates of Service maturing in 20 years.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 29</ref>\n\nThere were 3,662,374 Adjusted Service Certificates issued, with a combined face value of $3.64 billion (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|3.64|1924|r=0}}&nbsp;billion in {{Inflation/year|US-GDP}}).{{Inflation/fn|US-GDP}} Congress established a trust fund to receive 20 annual payments of $112 million that, with interest, would finance the 1945 disbursement of the $3.638 billion for the veterans. Meanwhile, veterans could borrow up to 22.5% of the certificate's face value from the fund; but in 1931, because of the [[Great Depression]], Congress increased the maximum value of such loans to 50% of the certificate's face value.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 37-8</ref> Although there was congressional support for the immediate redemption of the military service certificates, Hoover and Republican congressmen opposed such action and reasoned that the government would have to increase taxes to cover the costs of the payout and so any potential economic recovery would be slowed.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 34</ref>\n\nThe [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] continued to press the federal government to allow the early redemption of military service certificates.<ref>Stephen R. Ortiz, \"The 'New Deal' for Veterans: The Economy Act, the Veterans of Foreign Wars, and the Origins of the New Deal,\" ''Journal of Military History'', vol. 70 (2006), 434\u20135</ref>\n\nThe first march of the unemployed was [[Coxey's Army]] in 1894, when armies of men from various regions streamed to Washington as a \"living petition\" to demand that the federal government create jobs by investing in public infrastructure projects<ref>Donald L. McMurry, \"Coxey's Army\", 1930 (page cite needed).</ref> In January 1932, a march of 25,000 unemployed Pennsylvanians, dubbed \"[[James Renshaw Cox|Cox's Army]]\", had marched on Washington, D.C., the largest demonstration to date in the nation's capital, setting a precedent for future marches by the unemployed.{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}}\n\n==March==\n[[File:Bonus Army camp.jpg|thumb|Bonus Army Camp]]\nMost of the Bonus Army (Bonus Expeditionary Force or BEF) camped in a \"[[Hooverville]]\" on the Anacostia Flats, a swampy, muddy area across the [[Anacostia River]] from the federal core of Washington, just south of the [[11th Street Bridges]] (now Section C of [[Anacostia Park]]). Approximately 10,000 veterans, women and children lived in the shelters that they built from materials dragged out of a junk pile nearby, which included old lumber, packing boxes, and scrap tin covered with roofs of thatched straw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/snprelief4.htm|title=\"The Bonus Army\" Eyewitness to History (2000)}}</ref> The camps were tightly controlled by the veterans, who laid out streets, built sanitation facilities, and held daily parades. To live in the camps, veterans were required to register and to prove they had been honorably discharged.{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}} The Superintendent of the D.C. Police, [[Pelham D. Glassford]], worked with camp leaders to maintain order.\n\nOn June 15, 1932, the [[US House of Representatives]] passed the [[Wright Patman]] Bonus Bill to move forward the date for World War I veterans to receive their cash bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0609/23722.html|author=Glass, Andrew|date=2009|title=House passes bonus bill for WWI veterans, June 15, 1932|work=POLITICO|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> The Bonus Army massed at the [[U.S. Capitol]] on June 17 as the [[U.S. Senate]] voted on the Bonus Bill. The bill was defeated by a vote of 62\u201318.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff Correspondent |title=Senate Defeats Bonus Despite 10,000 Veterans Massed Around Capitol |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1932/06/18/100764065.html?pageNumber=1 |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |work=New York Times |issue=27,174|date=June 18, 1932 |ref=New York Times Historical Archive}}</ref>\n\n== Police shooting ==\n[[File:We want the bonus t.tif|thumb]]\nOn July 28, 1932, President Hoover ordered the Secretary of War to disperse the protesters. Towards the late afternoon, cavalry, infantry, tanks and machine guns pushed the \"Bonusers\" out of Washington. The troops injured more than one hundred marchers in the process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/politics/legal-and-political-magazines/bonus-army |title=The Bonus Army |work=Encyclopedia.com }}</ref> When the veterans moved back into the camp, police drew their revolvers and shot at the veterans, two of whom, William Hushka and Eric Carlson, died later.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/08/02/archives/veteran-dies-of-wounds-eric-carison-is-second-victim-of-thursdays.html |title=Veteran dies of wounds |date=August 2, 1932 |accessdate=August 30, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"timebattle\" />\n\nHushka (1895 \u2013 July 28, 1932) was an immigrant to the United States from [[Lithuania]]. When the US entered World War I in 1917, he sold his butcher shop in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], and joined the army. After the war, he lived in [[Chicago]].<ref name=timebattle>{{cite news |work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |url=http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,744107,00.html |title=Heroes: Battle of Washington |date=August 8, 1932 |accessdate=August 30, 2011 |quote=Last week William Hushka's Bonus for $528 suddenly became payable in full when a police bullet drilled him dead in the worst public disorder the capital has known in years. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025065911/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,744107,00.html |archivedate=2008-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hushka is buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=49209931|title=PFC William J Hushka (1895-1932) - Find A Grave Memorial}}</ref>\n\nCarlson (1894&nbsp;\u2013 August 2, 1932) was a veteran from [[Oakland, California]] who fought in the trenches of France in World War I.<ref name=timebattle /><ref>Mentioned in [http://www.answers.com/topic/the-march-of-the-bonus-army \"The March of the Bonus Army\" video], 30 min. Retrieved from answer.com 2011-2-4.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.semp.us/publications/biot_reader.php?BiotID=635 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090730180546/http://www.semp.us/publications/biot_reader.php?BiotID=635 |archivedate=2009-07-30 |title=Bonus Army Spectacle, U.S. Capital, 1932: What Really Happened. Section VI. Two Shootings at Glassford Camp |work=Suburban Emergency Management Project (SEMP), Biot Report #635 |date=July 18, 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-08 }}</ref> He was interred in Arlington National Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.communitywalk.com/location/bonus_expeditionary_force_martyrs_hushka__carlson_1932/info/2942468 |title=Bonus Expeditionary Force Martyrs Hushka & Carlson (1932) |work=DC Labor Map |accessdate=February 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 28 under prodding from the White House the D.C. Commissioners ordered Glassford to clear their buildings, rather than letting the protesters drift away as he had previously recommended. When the two veterans were shot, the Commissioners asked the White House for federal troops. Hoover passed the request to Secretary of War [[Patrick J. Hurley|Hurley]], who told MacArthur to take action.\n\n===Army Report===\nAn Army intelligence report claimed that the BEF intended to occupy the Capitol permanently and instigate fighting, as a signal for Communist uprisings in all major cities. It also conjectured that at least part of the Marine Corps garrison in Washington would side with the revolutionaries, hence Marine units eight blocks from the Capitol were never called upon. The report of July 5, 1932 by Conrad H. Lanza in upstate New York was not declassified until 1991.<ref>Lisio, Donald J. \u201cA Blunder Becomes Catastrophe: Hoover, the Legion, and the Bonus Army.\u201d The Wisconsin Magazine of History, vol. 51, no. 1, 1967, p. 40 JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/4634286.</ref>\n\n==Army intervention==\nAt 1:40 pm MacArthur ordered General Perry Miles to assemble troops on the Ellipse immediately south of the White House. Within the hour the 3rd Cavalry led by Patton, then a Major, crossed the Memorial Bridge, with the 12th Infantry arriving by steamer about an hour later. At 4 pm Miles told MacArthur that the troops were ready, and MacArthur (like Eisenhower, by now in service uniform), said that Hoover wanted him \"on hand\" to \"take the rap if ...\"\n\nAlthough the troops were ready, Hoover twice sent instructions to MacArthur not to cross the Anacostia bridge that night, both of which were ignored. Shortly after 9 p.m., MacArthur ordered Miles to cross the bridge and evict the Bonus Army from its encampment.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Jean Edward |authorlink=Jean Edward Smith |title=Eisenhower in War and Peace |publisher=Random House |date=2012 |location=New York |pages=109\u2013113 |url=|isbn=978-0-679-64429-3}}</ref>\n\nAt 4:45&nbsp;p.m., commanded by General [[Douglas MacArthur]], the [[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|12th Infantry Regiment]], [[Fort Howard (Maryland)|Fort Howard, Maryland]], and the [[3d Armored Cavalry Regiment (United States)|3rd Cavalry Regiment]], supported by six [[M1917 light tank]]s commanded by Maj. [[George S. Patton]], formed in Pennsylvania Avenue while thousands of civil service employees left work to line the street and watch. The Bonus Marchers, believing the troops were marching in their honor, cheered the troops until Patton ordered {{citation needed|date=March 2013}} the cavalry to charge them, which prompted the spectators to yell, \"Shame! Shame!\"{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}}\n\n[[File:Evictbonusarmy.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Shacks that members of the Bonus Army erected on the Anacostia Flats burning after its confrontation with the army.]]\n\nAfter the cavalry charged, the infantry, with fixed [[bayonets]] and [[tear gas]] ([[adamsite]], an arsenical vomiting agent) entered the camps, evicting veterans, families, and camp followers. The veterans fled across the Anacostia River to their largest camp, and Hoover ordered the assault stopped. MacArthur chose to ignore the president and ordered a new attack, claiming that the Bonus March was an attempt to overthrow the US government. 55 veterans were injured and 135 arrested.<ref name=timebattle /> A veteran's wife miscarried. When 12-week-old Bernard Myers died in the hospital after being caught in the tear gas attack, a government investigation reported he died of [[enteritis]], and a hospital spokesman said the tear gas \"didn't do it any good.\"<ref>Dickson and Allen, 182-3</ref>\n\nDuring the military operation, Major [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], later the 34th president of the United States, served as one of MacArthur's junior aides.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 170-4, 180</ref> Believing it wrong for the Army's highest-ranking officer to lead an action against fellow American war veterans, he strongly advised MacArthur against taking any public role: \"I told that dumb son-of-a-bitch not to go down there,\" he said later. \"I told him it was no place for the Chief of Staff.\"<ref name=Wukovits43>{{Cite book |title=Eisenhower |last=Wukovits |first=John F. |year=2006 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York |isbn=0-230-61394-2 |page=43 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=om5ZykQFGrwC&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=15 June 2011 }}</ref> Despite his misgivings, Eisenhower later wrote the Army's official incident report that endorsed MacArthur's conduct.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life |last=D'Este |first=Carlo |authorlink=Carlo D'Este |year=2002 |publisher=Henry Holt & Co. |location=New York |isbn=0-8050-5687-4 |page=223 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RCeteK7LEiYC&pg=PA223#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[Joe Angelo]], a decorated hero from the war who had saved Patton's life during the [[Meuse-Argonne offensive]] on September 26, 1918, approached him the day after to sway him. Patton, however, dismissed him quickly. This episode was said to represent the proverbial essence of the Bonus Army, each man the face of each side: Angelo the dejected loyal soldier; Patton the unmoved government official unconcerned with past loyalties.<ref>Hirshson, Stanley P. General Patton. Harper Collins Publishers 2002. New York, New York.</ref>\n\nThough the Bonus Army incident did not derail the careers of the military officers involved, it proved politically disastrous for Hoover, and it is considered a contributing factor to his losing the 1932 election in a landslide to [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historynet.com/the-bonus-army-war-in-washington.htm |via=Historynet.com |title=The 'Bonus Army' War in Washington |first=Wyatt |last=Kingseed |work=American History magazine |date=June 2004 |accessdate=31 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPolice Superintendent Glassford was not pleased with the decision to have the Army intervene, believing that the police could have handled the situation. He soon resigned as superintendent.\n\n[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]] released the movie ''[[Gabriel Over the White House]]'' in March 1933, the month Roosevelt was sworn in as president. Produced by [[William Randolph Hearst]]'s Cosmopolitan Pictures, it depicted a fictitious President Hammond who, in the film's opening scenes, refuses to deploy the military against a march of the unemployed and instead creates an \"Army of Construction\" to work on public works projects until the economy recovers.<ref>{{imdb title|tt0024044|Gabriel Over the White House}}</ref> First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] judged the movie's treatment of veterans superior to Hoover's.<ref name=cook>[[Blanche Wiesen Cook]], ''Eleanor Roosevelt'' (NY: Viking, 1999), vol. 2, 44\u20136</ref>\n\nDuring the presidential campaign of 1932, Roosevelt had opposed the veterans' bonus demands.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/10/17/archives/governor-lays-plans-for-trip-governor-to-state-antibonus-stand.html |title=Governor Lays Plans for Trip |date=October 17, 1932 |accessdate=December 18, 2010 }}</ref> A second bonus march planned for the following year in May by the \"National Liaison Committee of Washington,\" disavowed by the previous year's bonus army leadership, demanded that the Federal government provide marchers housing and food during their stay in the capital.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |title=New Bonus March Starts Tomorrow|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/05/09/105132790.pdf |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |work=New York Times|date=May 9, 1933 |ref=New York Times Archive}}</ref> Despite his opposition to the marcher's demand for immediate payment of the bonus, Roosevelt greeted them quite differently than did Hoover. The administration set up a special camp for the marchers at Fort Hunt, Virginia, providing forty field kitchens serving three meals a day, bus transportation to and from the capital, and entertainment in the form of military bands.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff Correspondent |title=Bonus Army Row Finally Adjusted |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/05/15/issue.html |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |work=New York Times |issue=LXXXII 27,505 |date=May 15, 1933 |ref=The New York Times Historical Archives}}</ref>\n\nAdministration officials, led by presidential confidant [[Louis Howe]], tried to negotiate an end to the protest. Roosevelt arranged for his wife, Eleanor, to visit the site unaccompanied. She lunched with the veterans and listened to them perform songs. She reminisced about her memories of seeing troops off to [[World War I]] and welcoming them home. The most that she could offer was a promise of positions in the newly created [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] (CCC).<ref name=cook/> One veteran commented, \"Hoover sent the army, Roosevelt sent his wife.\"{{sfn|Jenkins|2003|page=63}} In a press conference following her visit, the First Lady described her reception as courteous and praised the marchers, highlighting how comfortable she felt despite critics of the marchers who described them as communists and criminals.<ref name=cook/>\n\nRoosevelt later issued an executive order allowing the enrollment of 25,000 veterans in the CCC, exempting them from the normal requirement that applicants be unmarried and under the age of 25.<ref>{{cite book |isbn=9780307277947 |p=391 |title=Traitor to His Class: The Privileged Life and Radical Presidency of Franklin Delano Roosevelt |last1=Brands |first1=H. W. |year=2009 }}</ref> Congress, with Democrats holding majorities in both houses, passed the [[Adjusted Compensation Payment Act#Bonus Bills of 1930s|Adjusted Compensation Payment Act]] in 1936, authorizing the immediate payment of the $2 billion in World War I bonuses, and then overrode Roosevelt's veto of the measure.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/28/archives/bonus-bill-becomes-law-repassed-in-senate-7619-payment-will-be.html |title=Bonus Bill Becomes Law |date=January 28, 1936 |accessdate=December 20, 2010 }}</ref> The House vote was 324 to 61,<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/25/archives/house-swiftly-overrides-bonus-veto-by-roosevelt-senate-to-act-on.html |title=House Swiftly Overrides Bonus Veto by Roosevelt |date=January 25, 1936 |accessdate=September 3, 2011 }}</ref> and the Senate vote was 76 to 19.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/28/archives/bonus-bill-becomes-law-repassed-in-senate-7619-payment-will-be.html |title=Bonus Bill Becomes Law |date=January 28, 1936 |accessdate=September 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rallies and protest marches in Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[On-to-Ottawa Trek]] by Canadian veterans, 1935\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Burner, David. (1979). ''Herbert Hoover: A Public Life''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. {{ISBN|0-394-46134-7}}.\n* Daniels, Roger. (1971). ''The Bonus March: An Episode of the Great Depression''. Westport, CT: Greenwood Publishing. {{ISBN|0837151740}}\n* Dickson, Paul, and Thomas B. Allen. (2004). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=g5CEg9oOn4MC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false The Bonus Army: An American Epic]''. New York: Walker and Company. {{ISBN|0-8027-1440-4}}.\n* Dickson, Paul, and Thomas B. Allen. \"Marching On History,\" in ''Smithsonian'', February 2003\n* James, D. Clayton. (1970). ''The Years of MacArthur, Volume I, 1880\u20131941''. Boston: Houghton Mifflin. {{OCLC|36211265}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Jenkins|first=Roy|title=Franklin Delano Roosevelt|location=New York|publisher=Times Books|date=2003|isbn=9780805069594|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=USAUy_-KeH0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n* Lisio, Donald J. (1974). ''The President and Protest: Hoover, Conspiracy, and the Bonus Riot''. Columbia, MO: University of Missouri Press. {{ISBN|082620158X}}\n* Smith, Richard Norton. (1984). ''An Uncommon Man: The Triumph of Herbert Hoover''. New York: Simon & Schuster. {{ISBN|0-671-46034-X}}.\n* Liebovich, Louis W. (1994). ''Bylines in Despair: Herbert Hoover, the Great Depression, and the U.S. News Media'' {{ISBN|0-275-94843-9}}\n* Bennett, Michael J. (1999). ''When Dreams Come True: The GI Bill and the Making of Modern America'' {{ISBN|1-57488-218-X}}\n* Perret, Geoffrey (1996). \"MacArthur and the Marchers\" in ''MHQ: the Quarterly Journal of Military History''. Vol 8, No 2 American Historical Publication, Inc\n\n==Further reading==\n* Morrow, Felix. (1932). ''The Bonus March.'' International Pamphlets No. 31. New York: International Publishers. {{OCLC|12546840}}\n* Ortiz, Stephen R. 2006. \"Rethinking the Bonus March: Federal Bonus Policy, the Veterans of Foreign Wars, and the Origins of a Protest Movement\". ''Journal of Policy History''. 18, no. 3: 275\u2013303.\n* Rawl, Michael J. (2006). ''Anacostia Flats''. Baltimore: Publish America. {{ISBN|978-1-413-79778-7}}.\n* Smith, Gene. (1970). ''The Shattered Dream: Herbert Hoover and the Great Depression''. New York: William Morrow and Company. {{OCLC|76078}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bonus Army}}\n* {{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4494446 |title=Soldier Against Soldier: The Story of the Bonus Army |author=Sheilah Kast |date=February 13, 2005 |work=NPR: Weekend Edition Sunday}}\n* [http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/snprelief4.htm The Bonus Army] (EyeWitness to History)\n* [http://www.military.com/NewContent/0,13190,111104_BonusArmy,00.html Vets Owe Debt to WWI's \"Bonus Army] from [http://military.com military.com]\n* [http://vault.fbi.gov/Bonus%20March FBI file on the Bonus Army]\n* [http://www.worldwar1.com/dbc/bonusm.htm The Sad Tale of the Bonus Marchers]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/trm203.html Memory: The Bonus Army March], Library of Congress\n* [http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/paul-dickinson-thomas-b-allen-bonus-army/ Paul Dickson & Thomas B. Allen on '' The Bonus Army: An American Epic''], a lecture recorded at the [[Pritzker Military Museum & Library]]\n\n{{Coord|38|52|0.3|N|76|59|53|W|display=title}}\n{{Herbert Hoover}}\n{{American conflicts|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:1932 protests]]\n[[Category:1932 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of World War I in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1932]]\n[[Category:Great Depression in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of veterans' affairs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political repression in the United States]]\n[[Category:Protest marches in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1930s US veterans protest movement}}\n{{use mdy dates |date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict = Bonus Army Conflict\n|image = Bonus marchers 05510 2004 001 a.gif\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption = Bonus Army marchers (left) confront the police.\n|date = July 28, 1932\n|place = [[Washington D.C.]], [[United States]]\n|casus = Impoverishment of WWI veterans from the Depression\n|result = Bonus Army dispersed, demands rejected, Herbert Hoover loses [[1932 United States presidential election|1932 Presidential election]] \n|combatant1 = Bonus Army\n|combatant2 = {{flagicon|United States|1912}} [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]\n|commander1 = Walter W. Waters\n|commander2 = [[Herbert Hoover]]<br />[[Douglas MacArthur]]<br />[[George S. Patton]]\n|strength1 = 17,000 veterans<br />26,000 others\n|strength2 = 500 infantry<br />500 cavalry<br />6 [[M1917 light tank]]s<br />800 policemen\n|casualties1 = First day 2 dead; 1,017 injured,{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} total unknown \n|casualties2 = At least 69 police injured\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Aftermath of World War I}}\n\nThe '''Bonus Army''' was a group of 43,000 [[demonstration (protest)|demonstrators]] \u2013 made up of 17,000 U.S. [[World War I]] veterans, together with their families and affiliated groups \u2013 who gathered in [[Washington, D.C.]] in mid-1932 to demand early cash redemption of their service certificates. Organizers called the demonstrators the \"Bonus Expeditionary Force\", to echo the name of World War I's [[American Expeditionary Forces]], while the media referred to them as the \"Bonus Army\" or \"Bonus Marchers\". The demonstrators were led by Walter W. Waters, a former sergeant.\n\nMany of the war veterans had been out of work since the beginning of the [[Great Depression]]. The [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act]] of 1924 had awarded them bonuses in the form of certificates they could not redeem until 1948. Each certificate, issued to a qualified veteran soldier, bore a face value equal to the soldier's promised payment with compound interest. The principal demand of the Bonus Army was the immediate cash payment of their certificates.\n\nOn July 28, [[U.S. Attorney General]] [[William D. Mitchell]] ordered the veterans removed from all government property. Washington police met with resistance, shot at the protestors, and two veterans were wounded and later died. President [[Herbert Hoover]] then ordered the U.S. Army to clear the marchers' campsite. Army Chief of Staff General [[Douglas MacArthur]] commanded a contingent of infantry and cavalry, supported by six tanks. The Bonus Army marchers with their wives and children were driven out, and their shelters and belongings burned. \n \nA second, smaller Bonus March in 1933 at the start of the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] administration was defused in May with an offer of jobs with the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] at [[Fort Hunt, Virginia]], which most of the group accepted. Those who chose not to work for the CCC by the May 22 deadline were given transportation home.<ref>\"'Take Job in the Forest or Go Home' Is Alternative Given to Bonus Boys\", ''Middlesboro (Kentucky) Daily News'', May 17, 1933, p1; \"Bonus Marchers Weaken; Accept Jobs in Ax Corps\", ''Milwaukee Journal'', May 20, 1933, p1</ref> In 1936, Congress overrode President Roosevelt's veto and paid the veterans their bonus nine years early.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Bonus army on Capitol lawn cph.3a00515.jpg|thumb|Members of the Bonus Army camped out on the lawn of the U.S. Capitol building]]\nThe practice of war-time military bonuses began in 1776, as payment for the difference between what a soldier earned and what he could have earned had he not enlisted. The practice derived from British legislation passed in the 1592\u201393 session of Parliament to provide medical care and maintenance for disabled veterans and bonuses for serving soldiers. Similar legislation for disabled veterans later only progressively passed by the North American colonies, beginning with Virginia in 1624.{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}}\n\nIn 1781, most of the [[Continental Army]] was [[Demobilization|demobilized]]. Two years later, hundreds of [[Pennsylvania]] war veterans [[Pennsylvania Mutiny of 1783|marched on Philadelphia]], then the nation's capital, surrounded the State House, where the [[U.S. Congress]] was in session, and demanded back pay. Congress fled to [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and several weeks later, the [[U.S. Army]] expelled the war veterans from Philadelphia.{{citation needed|date = February 2018}}\n\nIn August 1776, Congress adopted the first national pension law providing half pay for life for disabled veterans. Considerable pressure was applied to expand benefits to match the British system for serving soldiers and sailors but had little support from the colonial government until mass desertions at the [[Battle of Valley Forge]] that threatened the existence of the [[Continental Army]] led [[George Washington]] to become a strong advocate. Congress progressively passed legislation from 1788 covering pensions and bonuses, eventually extending eligibility to widows in 1836.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graves|first1=Will|title=Pension Acts An Overview of Revolutionary War Pension and Bounty Land Legislation and the Southern Campaigns Pension Transcription Project|url=http://revwarapps.org/revwar-pension-acts.htm|website=Southern Campaigns Revolutionary War Pension Statements & Rosters|accessdate=29 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nBefore World War I, the soldiers' military service bonus (adjusted for rank) was land and money; a Continental Army private received {{convert|100|acre|ha}} and $80.00 (2017: $1,968.51) at war's end, while a major general received {{convert|1100|acre|ha}}. In 1855, Congress increased the land-grant minimum to {{convert|160|acre|ha}}, and reduced the eligibility requirements to fourteen days of military service or one battle; moreover, the bonus also applied to veterans of any Indian war. The provision of land eventually became a major political issue, particularly in Tennessee where almost 40% of arable land had been given to veterans as part of their bonus. By 1860, {{convert|73500000|acre|ha}} had been issued and lack of available arable land led to the program's abandonment and replacement with a cash-only system.{{citation needed|date = July 2017}} Breaking with tradition, the veterans of the [[Spanish\u2013American War]] did not receive a bonus and after [[World War I]], that became a political matter when they received only a $60 bonus. The [[American Legion]], created in 1919, led a political movement for an additional bonus.<ref name=greenberg/>\n\n[[File:USA-Cinderella-Stamp-1932 Pay the Bonus.jpg|thumb|left|[[Cinderella stamp]] (USA, 1932) supporting the Bonus Army]]\nOn May 15, 1924, President [[Calvin Coolidge]] vetoed a bill granting bonuses to veterans of World War I, saying: \"patriotism... bought and paid for is not patriotism.\" Congress overrode his veto a few days later,<ref name=greenberg>David Greenberg, ''Calvin Coolidge'' (NY: Henry Holt, 2006), 78\u20139</ref> enacting the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act]]. Each veteran was to receive a dollar for each day of domestic service, up to a maximum of $500 ({{Inflation|US|500|1924|r=-2|fmt=eq}}), and $1.25 for each day of overseas service, up to a maximum of $625 ({{Inflation|US|625|1924|r=-2|fmt=eq}}).{{Inflation/fn|US}} Amounts of $50 or less were immediately paid. All other amounts were issued as Certificates of Service maturing in 20 years.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 29</ref>\n\nThere were 3,662,374 Adjusted Service Certificates issued, with a combined face value of $3.64 billion (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|3.64|1924|r=0}}&nbsp;billion in {{Inflation/year|US-GDP}}).{{Inflation/fn|US-GDP}} Congress established a trust fund to receive 20 annual payments of $112 million that, with interest, would finance the 1945 disbursement of the $3.638 billion for the veterans. Meanwhile, veterans could borrow up to 22.5% of the certificate's face value from the fund; but in 1931, because of the [[Great Depression]], Congress increased the maximum value of such loans to 50% of the certificate's face value.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 37-8</ref> Although there was congressional support for the immediate redemption of the military service certificates, Hoover and Republican congressmen opposed such action and reasoned that the government would have to increase taxes to cover the costs of the payout and so any potential economic recovery would be slowed.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 34</ref>\n\nThe [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] continued to press the federal government to allow the early redemption of military service certificates.<ref>Stephen R. Ortiz, \"The 'New Deal' for Veterans: The Economy Act, the Veterans of Foreign Wars, and the Origins of the New Deal,\" ''Journal of Military History'', vol. 70 (2006), 434\u20135</ref>\n\nThe first march of the unemployed was [[Coxey's Army]] in 1894, when armies of men from various regions streamed to Washington as a \"living petition\" to demand that the federal government create jobs by investing in public infrastructure projects<ref>Donald L. McMurry, \"Coxey's Army\", 1930 (page cite needed).</ref> In January 1932, a march of 25,000 unemployed Pennsylvanians, dubbed \"[[James Renshaw Cox|Cox's Army]]\", had marched on Washington, D.C., the largest demonstration to date in the nation's capital, setting a precedent for future marches by the unemployed.{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}}\n\n==March==\n[[File:Bonus Army camp.jpg|thumb|Bonus Army Camp]]\nMost of the Bonus Army (Bonus Expeditionary Force or BEF) camped in a \"[[Hooverville]]\" on the Anacostia Flats, a swampy, muddy area across the [[Anacostia River]] from the federal core of Washington, just south of the [[11th Street Bridges]] (now Section C of [[Anacostia Park]]). Approximately 10,000 veterans, women and children lived in the shelters that they built from materials dragged out of a junk pile nearby, which included old lumber, packing boxes, and scrap tin covered with roofs of thatched straw.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/snprelief4.htm|title=\"The Bonus Army\" Eyewitness to History (2000)}}</ref> The camps were tightly controlled by the veterans, who laid out streets, built sanitation facilities, and held daily parades. To live in the camps, veterans were required to register and to prove they had been honorably discharged.{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}} The Superintendent of the D.C. Police, [[Pelham D. Glassford]], worked with camp leaders to maintain order.\n\nOn June 15, 1932, the [[US House of Representatives]] passed the [[Wright Patman]] Bonus Bill to move forward the date for World War I veterans to receive their cash bonus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0609/23722.html|author=Glass, Andrew|date=2009|title=House passes bonus bill for WWI veterans, June 15, 1932|work=POLITICO|accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> The Bonus Army massed at the [[U.S. Capitol]] on June 17 as the [[U.S. Senate]] voted on the Bonus Bill. The bill was defeated by a vote of 62\u201318.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff Correspondent |title=Senate Defeats Bonus Despite 10,000 Veterans Massed Around Capitol |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1932/06/18/100764065.html?pageNumber=1 |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |work=New York Times |issue=27,174|date=June 18, 1932 |ref=New York Times Historical Archive}}</ref>\n\n== Police shooting ==\n[[File:We want the bonus t.tif|thumb]]\nOn July 28, 1932, President Hoover ordered the Secretary of War to disperse the protesters. Towards the late afternoon, cavalry, infantry, tanks and machine guns pushed the \"Bonusers\" out of Washington. The troops injured more than one hundred marchers in the process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/politics/legal-and-political-magazines/bonus-army |title=The Bonus Army |work=Encyclopedia.com }}</ref> When the veterans moved back into the camp, police drew their revolvers and shot at the veterans, two of whom, William Hushka and Eric Carlson, died later.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/08/02/archives/veteran-dies-of-wounds-eric-carison-is-second-victim-of-thursdays.html |title=Veteran dies of wounds |date=August 2, 1932 |accessdate=August 30, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"timebattle\" />\n\nHushka (1895 \u2013 July 28, 1932) was an immigrant to the United States from [[Lithuania]]. When the US entered World War I in 1917, he sold his butcher shop in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], and joined the army. After the war, he lived in [[Chicago]].<ref name=timebattle>{{cite news |work=[[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |url=http://content.time.com/time/subscriber/article/0,33009,744107,00.html |title=Heroes: Battle of Washington |date=August 8, 1932 |accessdate=August 30, 2011 |quote=Last week William Hushka's Bonus for $528 suddenly became payable in full when a police bullet drilled him dead in the worst public disorder the capital has known in years. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025065911/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,744107,00.html |archivedate=2008-10-25 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hushka is buried in [[Arlington National Cemetery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=49209931|title=PFC William J Hushka (1895-1932) - Find A Grave Memorial}}</ref>\n\nCarlson (1894&nbsp;\u2013 August 2, 1932) was a veteran from [[Oakland, California]] who fought in the trenches of France in World War I.<ref name=timebattle /><ref>Mentioned in [http://www.answers.com/topic/the-march-of-the-bonus-army \"The March of the Bonus Army\" video], 30 min. Retrieved from answer.com 2011-2-4.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.semp.us/publications/biot_reader.php?BiotID=635 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090730180546/http://www.semp.us/publications/biot_reader.php?BiotID=635 |archivedate=2009-07-30 |title=Bonus Army Spectacle, U.S. Capital, 1932: What Really Happened. Section VI. Two Shootings at Glassford Camp |work=Suburban Emergency Management Project (SEMP), Biot Report #635 |date=July 18, 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-08 }}</ref> He was interred in Arlington National Cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.communitywalk.com/location/bonus_expeditionary_force_martyrs_hushka__carlson_1932/info/2942468 |title=Bonus Expeditionary Force Martyrs Hushka & Carlson (1932) |work=DC Labor Map |accessdate=February 8, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn July 28 under prodding from the White House the D.C. Commissioners ordered Glassford to clear their buildings, rather than letting the protesters drift away as he had previously recommended. When the two veterans were shot, the Commissioners asked the White House for federal troops. Hoover passed the request to Secretary of War [[Patrick J. Hurley|Hurley]], who told MacArthur to take action.\n\n===Army Report===\nAn Army intelligence report claimed that the BEF intended to occupy the Capitol permanently and instigate fighting, as a signal for Communist uprisings in all major cities. It also conjectured that at least part of the Marine Corps garrison in Washington would side with the revolutionaries, hence Marine units eight blocks from the Capitol were never called upon. The report of July 5, 1932 by Conrad H. Lanza in upstate New York was not declassified until 1991.<ref>Lisio, Donald J. \u201cA Blunder Becomes Catastrophe: Hoover, the Legion, and the Bonus Army.\u201d The Wisconsin Magazine of History, vol. 51, no. 1, 1967, p. 40 JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/4634286.</ref>\n\n==Army intervention==\nAt 1:40 pm MacArthur ordered General Perry Miles to assemble troops on the Ellipse immediately south of the White House. Within the hour the 3rd Cavalry led by Patton, then a Major, crossed the Memorial Bridge, with the 12th Infantry arriving by steamer about an hour later. At 4 pm Miles told MacArthur that the troops were ready, and MacArthur (like Eisenhower, by now in service uniform), said that Hoover wanted him \"on hand\" to \"take the rap if ...\"\n\nAlthough the troops were ready, Hoover twice sent instructions to MacArthur not to cross the Anacostia bridge that night, both of which were ignored. Shortly after 9 p.m., MacArthur ordered Miles to cross the bridge and evict the Bonus Army from its encampment.<ref>{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Jean Edward |authorlink=Jean Edward Smith |title=Eisenhower in War and Peace |publisher=Random House |date=2012 |location=New York |pages=109\u2013113 |url=|isbn=978-0-679-64429-3}}</ref>\n\nAt 4:45&nbsp;p.m., commanded by General [[Douglas MacArthur]], the [[12th Infantry Regiment (United States)|12th Infantry Regiment]], [[Fort Howard (Maryland)|Fort Howard, Maryland]], and the [[3d Armored Cavalry Regiment (United States)|3rd Cavalry Regiment]], supported by six [[M1917 light tank]]s commanded by Maj. [[George S. Patton]], formed in Pennsylvania Avenue while thousands of civil service employees left work to line the street and watch. The Bonus Marchers, believing the troops were marching in their honor, cheered the troops until Patton ordered {{citation needed|date=March 2013}} the cavalry to charge them, which prompted the spectators to yell, \"Shame! Shame!\"{{Citation needed|date = July 2016}}\n\n[[File:Evictbonusarmy.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Shacks that members of the Bonus Army erected on the Anacostia Flats burning after its confrontation with the army.]]\n\nAfter the cavalry charged, the infantry, with fixed [[bayonets]] and [[tear gas]] ([[adamsite]], an arsenical vomiting agent) entered the camps, evicting veterans, families, and camp followers. The veterans fled across the Anacostia River to their largest camp, and Hoover ordered the assault stopped. MacArthur chose to ignore the president and ordered a new attack, claiming that the Bonus March was an attempt to overthrow the US government. 55 veterans were injured and 135 arrested.<ref name=timebattle /> A veteran's wife miscarried. When 12-week-old Bernard Myers died in the hospital after being caught in the tear gas attack, a government investigation reported he died of [[enteritis]], and a hospital spokesman said the tear gas \"didn't do it any good.\"<ref>Dickson and Allen, 182-3</ref>\n\nDuring the military operation, Major [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], later the 34th president of the United States, served as one of MacArthur's junior aides.<ref>Dickson and Allen, 170-4, 180</ref> Believing it wrong for the Army's highest-ranking officer to lead an action against fellow American war veterans, he strongly advised MacArthur against taking any public role: \"I told that dumb son-of-a-bitch not to go down there,\" he said later. \"I told him it was no place for the Chief of Staff.\"<ref name=Wukovits43>{{Cite book |title=Eisenhower |last=Wukovits |first=John F. |year=2006 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |location=New York |isbn=0-230-61394-2 |page=43 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=om5ZykQFGrwC&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=15 June 2011 }}</ref> Despite his misgivings, Eisenhower later wrote the Army's official incident report that endorsed MacArthur's conduct.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Eisenhower: A Soldier's Life |last=D'Este |first=Carlo |authorlink=Carlo D'Este |year=2002 |publisher=Henry Holt & Co. |location=New York |isbn=0-8050-5687-4 |page=223 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RCeteK7LEiYC&pg=PA223#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=15 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[Joe Angelo]], a decorated hero from the war who had saved Patton's life during the [[Meuse-Argonne offensive]] on September 26, 1918, approached him the day after to sway him. Patton, however, dismissed him quickly. This episode was said to represent the proverbial essence of the Bonus Army, each man the face of each side: Angelo the dejected loyal soldier; Patton the unmoved government official unconcerned with past loyalties.<ref>Hirshson, Stanley P. General Patton. Harper Collins Publishers 2002. New York, New York.</ref>\n\nThough the Bonus Army incident did not derail the careers of the military officers involved, it proved politically disastrous for Hoover, and it is considered a contributing factor to his losing the 1932 election in a landslide to [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historynet.com/the-bonus-army-war-in-washington.htm |via=Historynet.com |title=The 'Bonus Army' War in Washington |first=Wyatt |last=Kingseed |work=American History magazine |date=June 2004 |accessdate=31 Jan 2018 }}</ref>\n\nPolice Superintendent Glassford was not pleased with the decision to have the Army intervene, believing that the police could have handled the situation. He soon resigned as superintendent.\n\n[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]] released the movie ''[[Gabriel Over the White House]]'' in March 1933, the month Roosevelt was sworn in as president. Produced by [[William Randolph Hearst]]'s Cosmopolitan Pictures, it depicted a fictitious President Hammond who, in the film's opening scenes, refuses to deploy the military against a march of the unemployed and instead creates an \"Army of Construction\" to work on public works projects until the economy recovers.<ref>{{imdb title|tt0024044|Gabriel Over the White House}}</ref> First Lady [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] judged the movie's treatment of veterans superior to Hoover's.<ref name=cook>[[Blanche Wiesen Cook]], ''Eleanor Roosevelt'' (NY: Viking, 1999), vol. 2, 44\u20136</ref>\n\nDuring the presidential campaign of 1932, Roosevelt had opposed the veterans' bonus demands.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/10/17/archives/governor-lays-plans-for-trip-governor-to-state-antibonus-stand.html |title=Governor Lays Plans for Trip |date=October 17, 1932 |accessdate=December 18, 2010 }}</ref> A second bonus march planned for the following year in May by the \"National Liaison Committee of Washington,\" disavowed by the previous year's bonus army leadership, demanded that the Federal government provide marchers housing and food during their stay in the capital.<ref>{{cite news |last1= |title=New Bonus March Starts Tomorrow|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/05/09/105132790.pdf |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |work=New York Times|date=May 9, 1933 |ref=New York Times Archive}}</ref> Despite his opposition to the marcher's demand for immediate payment of the bonus, Roosevelt greeted them quite differently than did Hoover. The administration set up a special camp for the marchers at Fort Hunt, Virginia, providing forty field kitchens serving three meals a day, bus transportation to and from the capital, and entertainment in the form of military bands.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff Correspondent |title=Bonus Army Row Finally Adjusted |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1933/05/15/issue.html |accessdate=December 26, 2018 |work=New York Times |issue=LXXXII 27,505 |date=May 15, 1933 |ref=The New York Times Historical Archives}}</ref>\n\nAdministration officials, led by presidential confidant [[Louis Howe]], tried to negotiate an end to the protest. Roosevelt arranged for his wife, Eleanor, to visit the site unaccompanied. She lunched with the veterans and listened to them perform songs. She reminisced about her memories of seeing troops off to [[World War I]] and welcoming them home. The most that she could offer was a promise of positions in the newly created [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] (CCC).<ref name=cook/> One veteran commented, \"Hoover sent the army, Roosevelt sent his wife.\"{{sfn|Jenkins|2003|page=63}} In a press conference following her visit, the First Lady described her reception as courteous and praised the marchers, highlighting how comfortable she felt despite critics of the marchers who described them as communists and criminals.<ref name=cook/>\n\nRoosevelt later issued an executive order allowing the enrollment of 25,000 veterans in the CCC, exempting them from the normal requirement that applicants be unmarried and under the age of 25.<ref>{{cite book |isbn=9780307277947 |p=391 |title=Traitor to His Class: The Privileged Life and Radical Presidency of Franklin Delano Roosevelt |last1=Brands |first1=H. W. |year=2009 }}</ref> Congress, with Democrats holding majorities in both houses, passed the [[Adjusted Compensation Payment Act#Bonus Bills of 1930s|Adjusted Compensation Payment Act]] in 1936, authorizing the immediate payment of the $2 billion in World War I bonuses, and then overrode Roosevelt's veto of the measure.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/28/archives/bonus-bill-becomes-law-repassed-in-senate-7619-payment-will-be.html |title=Bonus Bill Becomes Law |date=January 28, 1936 |accessdate=December 20, 2010 }}</ref> The House vote was 324 to 61,<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/25/archives/house-swiftly-overrides-bonus-veto-by-roosevelt-senate-to-act-on.html |title=House Swiftly Overrides Bonus Veto by Roosevelt |date=January 25, 1936 |accessdate=September 3, 2011 }}</ref> and the Senate vote was 76 to 19.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/01/28/archives/bonus-bill-becomes-law-repassed-in-senate-7619-payment-will-be.html |title=Bonus Bill Becomes Law |date=January 28, 1936 |accessdate=September 3, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of rallies and protest marches in Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[On-to-Ottawa Trek]] by Canadian veterans, 1935\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Burner, David. (1979). ''Herbert Hoover: A Public Life''. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. {{ISBN|0-394-46134-7}}.\n* Daniels, Roger. (1971). ''The Bonus March: An Episode of the Great Depression''. Westport, CT: Greenwood Publishing. {{ISBN|0837151740}}\n* Dickson, Paul, and Thomas B. Allen. (2004). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=g5CEg9oOn4MC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false The Bonus Army: An American Epic]''. New York: Walker and Company. {{ISBN|0-8027-1440-4}}.\n* Dickson, Paul, and Thomas B. Allen. \"Marching On History,\" in ''Smithsonian'', February 2003\n* James, D. Clayton. (1970). ''The Years of MacArthur, Volume I, 1880\u20131941''. Boston: Houghton Mifflin. {{OCLC|36211265}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Jenkins|first=Roy|title=Franklin Delano Roosevelt|location=New York|publisher=Times Books|date=2003|isbn=9780805069594|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=USAUy_-KeH0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}\n* Lisio, Donald J. (1974). ''The President and Protest: Hoover, Conspiracy, and the Bonus Riot''. Columbia, MO: University of Missouri Press. {{ISBN|082620158X}}\n* Smith, Richard Norton. (1984). ''An Uncommon Man: The Triumph of Herbert Hoover''. New York: Simon & Schuster. {{ISBN|0-671-46034-X}}.\n* Liebovich, Louis W. (1994). ''Bylines in Despair: Herbert Hoover, the Great Depression, and the U.S. News Media'' {{ISBN|0-275-94843-9}}\n* Bennett, Michael J. (1999). ''When Dreams Come True: The GI Bill and the Making of Modern America'' {{ISBN|1-57488-218-X}}\n* Perret, Geoffrey (1996). \"MacArthur and the Marchers\" in ''MHQ: the Quarterly Journal of Military History''. Vol 8, No 2 American Historical Publication, Inc\n\n==Further reading==\n* Morrow, Felix. (1932). ''The Bonus March.'' International Pamphlets No. 31. New York: International Publishers. {{OCLC|12546840}}\n* Ortiz, Stephen R. 2006. \"Rethinking the Bonus March: Federal Bonus Policy, the Veterans of Foreign Wars, and the Origins of a Protest Movement\". ''Journal of Policy History''. 18, no. 3: 275\u2013303.\n* Rawl, Michael J. (2006). ''Anacostia Flats''. Baltimore: Publish America. {{ISBN|978-1-413-79778-7}}.\n* Smith, Gene. (1970). ''The Shattered Dream: Herbert Hoover and the Great Depression''. New York: William Morrow and Company. {{OCLC|76078}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bonus Army}}\n* {{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4494446 |title=Soldier Against Soldier: The Story of the Bonus Army |author=Sheilah Kast |date=February 13, 2005 |work=NPR: Weekend Edition Sunday}}\n* [http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/snprelief4.htm The Bonus Army] (EyeWitness to History)\n* [http://www.military.com/NewContent/0,13190,111104_BonusArmy,00.html Vets Owe Debt to WWI's \"Bonus Army] from [http://military.com military.com]\n* [http://vault.fbi.gov/Bonus%20March FBI file on the Bonus Army]\n* [http://www.worldwar1.com/dbc/bonusm.htm The Sad Tale of the Bonus Marchers]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/trm203.html Memory: The Bonus Army March], Library of Congress\n* [http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/paul-dickinson-thomas-b-allen-bonus-army/ Paul Dickson & Thomas B. Allen on '' The Bonus Army: An American Epic''], a lecture recorded at the [[Pritzker Military Museum & Library]]\n\n{{Coord|38|52|0.3|N|76|59|53|W|display=title}}\n{{Herbert Hoover}}\n{{American conflicts|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:1932 protests]]\n[[Category:1932 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Aftermath of World War I in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1932]]\n[[Category:Great Depression in the United States]]\n[[Category:History of veterans' affairs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political repression in the United States]]\n[[Category:Protest marches in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "67.86.4.205", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonus_Army"}
{"title_page": "Ken Kwapis", "text_new": "{{short description|American film and television director and scriptwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ken Kwapis\n| residence   = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1957|8|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[East St. Louis, Illinois]], U.S.\n| birth_name  = Kenneth William Kwapis\n| known       = \n| occupation  = [[film director|Film]] and [[television director]], [[screenwriter]]\n| spouse      = [[Marisa Silver]]\n| children    = 2\n| relations   = \n}}\n\n'''Kenneth William Kwapis''' (born August 17, 1957) is an [[Americans|American]] [[film director|film]] and [[television director]] and [[screenwriter]]. He specialized in the [[Single-camera setup|single-camera]] [[sitcom]] in the 1990s and 2000s and has directed feature films such as ''[[Sesame Street Presents: Follow That Bird]]'' (1985), ''[[The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)|The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]'' (2005), and ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That into You]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite news |first=Todd |last=Longwell |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001956037 |title=Big 'Mac' |work=Hollywood Reporter |date=2 February 2006 |accessdate=2006-03-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060513122208/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001956037 |archivedate=13 May 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKwapis was born in [[East St. Louis, Illinois|East St. Louis]], [[Illinois]], and grew up in neighboring [[Belleville, Illinois|Belleville]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Carla Keller |last=Anderson |url=http://www.belleville.com/mld/belleville/living/community/11492905.htm |title=Before they were stars... |work=Belleville News-Democrat |date=29 April 2005 |accessdate=2006-03-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051028053917/http://www.belleville.com/mld/belleville/living/community/11492905.htm |archivedate=28 October 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is the son of Marge (Wells) and Bruno Walter Kwapis, who was an oral surgeon.<ref>{{cite news|title=ABOUT KEN KWAPIS |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ND&s_site=belleville&p_multi=ND&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12649FAD74D97310&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |newspaper=Belleville News-Democrat |date=February 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnd.com/2010/09/19/1406142/caring-for-the-injured.html |title=Our War: Korea ... Belleville surgeon Dr. Bruno Kwapis rebuilt faces of war &#124; Belleville News-Democrat |publisher=Bnd.com |date=2010-09-19 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/belleville/obituary.aspx?pid=175700732 |title=Bruno W. Kwapis Obituary: View Bruno Kwapis's Obituary by Belleville News-Democrat |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> He is of Polish descent<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/102576572.html?dids=102576572:102576572&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+17%2C+1991&author=By+Martin+Kasindorf.+STAFF+CORRESPONDENT&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=What+They're+Saying+He+Said%2C+She+Said'+chronicles+the+war+of+the+sexes+from+both+sides.+Guess+What%3A+The+viewpoints+differ.&pqatl=google | title=What They're Saying He Said, She Said' chronicles the war of the sexes from both sides. Guess What: The viewpoints differ | first=Martin | last=Kasindorf | date=February 17, 1991 | work=Newsday}}</ref> and was raised [[Catholic]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/features/columns/e3ia91b17b15e3f3af5c176436398b57481 |url-status=dead |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Martin A. |last=Grove |title=Sick of fantasies? 'Wed' offers return to reality |date=June 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915080908/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/features/columns/e3ia91b17b15e3f3af5c176436398b57481 |archivedate=September 15, 2007}}</ref> attending the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] preparatory academy [[St. Louis University High School]].\n\nHe earned a [[Bachelor's degree]] at [[Northwestern University]]'s School of Speech, after which he traveled west to enroll in the [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] program at the [[USC School of Cinema-Television]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Notable Alumni |work=USC School of Cinema-Television |url=http://www-cntv.usc.edu/friends_alumni/alumni-notable.cfm |accessdate=2006-03-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060216024619/http://www-cntv.usc.edu/friends_alumni/alumni-notable.cfm |archivedate=2006-02-16 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKwapis' twenty-four-minute thesis film, ''For Heaven's Sake'', won the [[Student Academy Award]] in 1982. The film is a contemporary adaptation of [[Mozart]]'s one-act [[opera]] ''[[Der Schauspieldirektor]]'' (''The Impresario'').\n\n==Family==\nKwapis is married to [[Marisa Silver]], with whom he has two sons.<ref name=keeping>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/01/movies/01roch.html | title = Keeping Things Human Size, Despite the Stars | first = Margy | last = Rochlin | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = January 30, 2009 | accessdate = November 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=pifm>{{cite web | url = http://www.pifmagazine.com/2010/07/marisa-silver-interview/ | title = Marisa Silver | first = Derek | last = Alger | work = Pif Magazine | date = July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1980s===\nIn 1983, Kwapis directed ''Revenge of the Nerd'' for [[CBS]]' ''Afternoon Playhouse'', followed by ''Summer Switch'' for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''Afterschool Special''. Starring [[Robert Klein]], ''Summer Switch'' is an adaptation of the novel of the same name, the sequel to a young adult fantasy, ''[[Freaky Friday]]''. For the Scholastic Book Company, Kwapis directed his first feature film ''[[The Beniker Gang]]'', starring [[Andrew McCarthy]].\n\nKwapis' next film was ''[[Sesame Street Presents Follow That Bird]]'' ([[Warner Bros.]], 1985). The film was the big-screen debut of the [[Sesame Street]] ensemble ([[Big Bird]], [[Oscar the Grouch]], [[Count von Count|The Count]], [[Bert & Ernie]], et al.). ''Follow That Bird'' tells the story of Big Bird's quest to live with a family of his own kind; namely, birds. A social worker arranges for Big Bird to move in with a family of Dodo Birds in Oceanview, Illinois.\n\nIn 1987, Kwapis made his [[prime time]] television debut, directing an installment of [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Amazing Stories (1985 TV series)|Amazing Stories]]''.\n\nKwapis' second feature ''[[Vibes (film)|Vibes]]'' ([[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]], 1988) was made under [[Ron Howard]] and [[Brian Grazer]]'s fledgling [[Imagine Entertainment|Imagine]] banner. Written by [[Lowell Ganz]] and [[Babaloo Mandel]], ''Vibes'' is the tale of two psychics ([[Jeff Goldblum]] and [[Cyndi Lauper]]) who are enlisted by a fortune hunter ([[Peter Falk]]) to divine the whereabouts of a treasure hidden in the [[Andes]]. The film was shot on location in [[Ecuador]], and features a pan pipe-flavored score by [[James Horner]].\n\n===1990s===\nKwapis began the 1990s with a feature-film project, ''[[He Said, She Said (film)|He Said, She Said]]'' ([[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]], 1991)\u2014co-directed by his now-wife [[Marisa Silver]]. The film, written by [[Brian Hohlfeld]], is a romantic comedy in which the same events are recounted twice\u2014once from each partner's point of view. The woman's ([[Elizabeth Perkins]]) portion of the film was directed by Silver and the man's ([[Kevin Bacon]]) by Kwapis. The film also features [[Sharon Stone]] and [[Nathan Lane]]. Soon after the release of ''He Said, She Said'', the film's title (coined by Silver) entered the vernacular as shorthand for any situation involving \"testimony in direct conflict\".<ref>For the etymology of the phrase, \"He said, she said\", see William Safire, \"On Language; He-Said, She-Said\", https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/12/magazine/on-language-he-said-she-said.html .</ref>\n\nKwapis then moved into series television, directing the pilot of [[HBO]]'s comedy ''[[The Larry Sanders Show]]''. He directed twelve episodes of the series.\n\nKwapis also contributed two episodes to the sci-fi series ''[[Eerie, Indiana]]''.\n\nKwapis' fourth feature, ''[[Dunston Checks In]]'' ([[Twentieth Century Fox]], 1996), stars [[Jason Alexander]] as the manager of a grand hotel in [[New York City]], which is owned and operated by a tyrant in the [[Leona Helmsley]] mold ([[Faye Dunaway]]). An aristocrat of dubious origin ([[Rupert Everett]]) checks into the hotel with an orangutan jewel thief.\n\nKwapis' next film, ''[[The Beautician and the Beast]]'' ([[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]], 1997), evokes the Ruritanian comedies of [[Ernst Lubitsch]]. [[Fran Drescher]] plays a New York cosmetologist who is mistakenly hired to tutor the children of the despotic president of Slovetzia ([[Timothy Dalton]]).\n\nIn the late 1990s, Kwapis directed two episodes of [[NBC]]'s short-lived cult following show ''[[Freaks and Geeks]]''.\n\n===2000s===\nIn the first decade of the 2000s, Kwapis directed nineteen episodes of [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', earning a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for his work as a producer-director.\n\nIn 2001, Kwapis helped develop ''[[The Bernie Mac Show]]'' for Fox, directing the pilot and ten additional episodes, including the series finale, \"Bernie's Angels\". Also for Fox, Kwapis was one of the main creative forces behind ''[[Grounded for Life]]'', a hybrid comedy combining single- and multi-camera techniques. Kwapis experimented with the form even further in the pilot of ''[[Watching Ellie]]'', [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]]' follow-up to ''[[Seinfeld]]''. The distinctive pilot has a story that unfolds in real time, with an on-screen clock. Playing the role of Ellie's ex-boyfriend is [[Steve Carell]], with whom Kwapis would shortly collaborate on his next major project.\n\nIn 2005, Kwapis worked on ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' which was an adaptation of the [[BBC]] [[mockumentary]] of the [[The Office (UK TV series)|same name]]. He directed the [[Pilot (The Office)|pilot]] and twelve additional episodes, including the 100th episode of the series, \"Company Picnic\". His work on the third-season premiere, \"[[Gay Witch Hunt]]\", earned him a second [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]]. He also directed the [[Finale (The Office)|series finale]].\n\nFor Showtime Independent Pictures, Kwapis wrote and directed ''[[Sexual Life]]'' (2005), loosely based on [[Arthur Schnitzler]]'s satiric story taking place in [[fin-de-si\u00e8cle]] [[Vienna]], ''[[La Ronde (play)|La Ronde]]''.\n\nKwapis' next feature was another adaptation, ''[[Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]'' ([[Warner Bros.]], 2006), based on the bestselling young adult novel by [[Ann Brashares]]. ''Sisterhood'', a coming-of-age story about four sixteen-year-old friends, stars [[Amber Tamblyn]], [[Alexis Bledel]], [[America Ferrera]], and [[Blake Lively]] (her screen debut).\n\nHis next feature, ''[[License to Wed]]'' (Warner Bros., 2007), follows a young couple ([[Mandy Moore]] and [[John Krasinski]]), as they embark upon an unorthodox pre-marital course, devised by a highly mischievous and somewhat perverse minister ([[Robin Williams]]). Designed to determine their compatibility, the course compresses the first ten years of marriage into one week.\n\nKwapis' follow-up was another look at romantic entanglements, ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That into You]]'' ([[New Line Cinema]], 2009). The film is adapted from the bestselling advice book by [[Greg Behrendt]] and [[Liz Tuccillo]], which encouraged people to learn to read romantic signals correctly. The film stars [[Ben Affleck]], [[Jennifer Aniston]], [[Drew Barrymore]], [[Jennifer Connelly]], [[Kevin Connolly (actor)|Kevin Connolly]], [[Bradley Cooper]], [[Ginnifer Goodwin]], [[Scarlett Johansson]], and [[Justin Long]].\n\n===2010s===\nKwapis launched his seventh series and directed his tenth feature film in 2010. He was the executive producer and director of the pilot of ''[[Outsourced (TV series)|Outsourced]]'', a half-hour comedy for NBC. Adapted from the 2006 [[Outsourced (film)|feature film of the same name]], ''Outsourced'' tells the story of a Kansas City-based novelties company that ships all of its customer service jobs to [[India]]. The one American employee not to be fired, Todd Dempsey ([[Ben Rappaport]]), goes to [[Mumbai]] to oversee the call center.\n\nFor [[Working Title Films]], and [[Universal Pictures]], Kwapis directed the rescue adventure ''[[Big Miracle]]'', starring [[Drew Barrymore]] and [[John Krasinski]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3ia63351ea832b17bfd91d511a23a7b04c |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609112836/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3ia63351ea832b17bfd91d511a23a7b04c |archivedate=June 9, 2009|title=Director Ken Kwapis hunts 'Whales'}}</ref> Based on a real event that took place in 1988, the film tells the tale of a small town newsman (Krasinski) and a [[Greenpeace]] volunteer (Barrymore) who are joined by rival world superpowers to save a family of [[gray whale]]s trapped in the ice of the [[Arctic Ocean]]. The film was shot during fall 2010 in Alaska and released in 2012.\n\nIn 2013, nine years after bringing the [[Pilot (The Office)|pilot]] to U.S. television, Kwapis directed the [[Finale (The Office)|series finale]] of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''. He also produced the half-hour [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] pilot ''[[Happyish]]'', written by [[Shalom Auslander]] and starring [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]]. The project stalled after Hoffman's death, but was eventually recast with [[Steve Coogan]]. It made its debut on Showtime in April 2015 and, in addition to producing, Kwapis directed four of its episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Friedlander|first1=Whitney|title=Showtime Cancels \u2018Happyish\u2019 After One Season|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/happyish-canceled-showtime-1201548349/|website=Variety|accessdate=2 November 2016|date=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kwapis directed the feature film ''[[A Walk in the Woods (film)|A Walk in the Woods]]'', based on the [[A Walk in the Woods (book)|bestselling travel memoir]] by [[Bill Bryson]]. The film stars [[Robert Redford]] and [[Nick Nolte]] as two old friends who decide to walk the 2,100-mile [[Appalachian Trail]]. The film, which was co-produced by Redford, also stars [[Emma Thompson]] and [[Mary Steenburgen]], and premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2015. ''A Walk in the Woods'' was released by Broad Green on September 2, 2015.\n\nRecently, Kwapis returned to single-camera half-hour comedy and directed four episodes of [[Tig Notaro]]'s semi-autobiographical [[Internet television]] series, ''[[One Mississippi (TV series)|One Mississippi]]''\u2014two per season in 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0477129/#director |title=Ken Kwapis - IMDb |publisher=imdb.com |date=1957-08-17 |accessdate=2017-09-21}}</ref> The show was produced by [[Amazon Studios]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Dominic Patten, Nellie|title=\u2018One Mississippi\u2019, \u2018I Love Dick\u2019 & \u2018Jean-Claude Van Johnson\u2019 Canceled By Amazon|url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/one-mississippi-i-love-dick-jean-claude-van-johnson-canceled-amazon-1202245153/|website=Deadline|accessdate=January 18, 2018|date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> He has also directed episodes of ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]'', a comedy starring and produced by [[Drew Barrymore]] and first released by Netflix on February 3, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/ken-kwapis/credits/182465/916115/?from=916115 |title=Ken Kwapis |website=TV Guide |orig-year=2017 |access-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Feature films===\n* ''[[A Walk in the Woods (film)|A Walk in the Woods]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Big Miracle]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That into You]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[License to Wed]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)|The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Sexual Life]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Beautician and the Beast]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Dunston Checks In]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[He Said, She Said (film)|He Said, She Said]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Vibes (film)|Vibes]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Sesame Street Presents Follow That Bird]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[The Beniker Gang]]'' (1985)\n\n===Notable episodic television work (directing)===\n{{Div col}}\n*''BlackAF'' (2020)\n*''The Dangerous Book for Boys'' (2018)\n*''Santa Clarita Diet'' (2017-2019)\n*''One Mississippi'' (2016-2017)\n*''Happyish'' (2015)\n*''The Office'' (2005-2013)\n*''Outsourced'' (2010)\n*''Parks and Recreation'' (2010)\n*''The Bernie Mac Show'' (2001-2006)\n*''Malcolm in the Middle'' (2000-2004)\n*''Watching Ellie'' (2002)\n*''Grounded for Life'' (2001)\n*''ER'' (1999-2000)\n*''Freaks and Geeks'' (1999-2000)\n*''The Wonderful World of Disney'' (1998)\n*''Bakersfield P.D.'' (1993)\n*''The Larry Sanders Show'' (1992-1993)\n*''Eerie, Indiana'' (1992)\n*''Amazing Stories'' (1987)\n*''ABC Afterschool Specials'' (1984)\n*''CBS Afternoon Playhouse'' (1983)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0477129|Ken Kwapis}}\n\n{{Ken Kwapis}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kwapis, Ken}}\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Belleville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University School of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American film and television director and scriptwriter}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Ken Kwapis\n| residence   = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1957|8|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[East St. Louis, Illinois]], U.S.\n| birth_name  = Kenneth William Kwapis\n| known       = \n| occupation  = [[film director|Film]] and [[television director]], [[screenwriter]]\n| spouse      = [[Marisa Silver]]\n| children    = 2\n| relations   = \n}}\n\n'''Kenneth William Kwapis''' (born August 17, 1957) is an [[Americans|American]] [[film director|film]] and [[television director]] and [[screenwriter]]. He specialized in the [[Single-camera setup|single-camera]] [[sitcom]] in the 1990s and 2000s and has directed feature films such as ''[[Sesame Street Presents: Follow That Bird]]'' (1985), ''[[The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)|The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]'' (2005), and ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That into You]]'' (2009).<ref>{{cite news |first=Todd |last=Longwell |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001956037 |title=Big 'Mac' |work=Hollywood Reporter |date=2 February 2006 |accessdate=2006-03-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060513122208/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/feature_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001956037 |archivedate=13 May 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKwapis was born in [[East St. Louis, Illinois|East St. Louis]], [[Illinois]], and grew up in neighboring [[Belleville, Illinois|Belleville]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Carla Keller |last=Anderson |url=http://www.belleville.com/mld/belleville/living/community/11492905.htm |title=Before they were stars... |work=Belleville News-Democrat |date=29 April 2005 |accessdate=2006-03-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051028053917/http://www.belleville.com/mld/belleville/living/community/11492905.htm |archivedate=28 October 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He is the son of Marge (Wells) and Bruno Walter Kwapis, who was an oral surgeon.<ref>{{cite news|title=ABOUT KEN KWAPIS |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ND&s_site=belleville&p_multi=ND&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=12649FAD74D97310&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |newspaper=Belleville News-Democrat |date=February 8, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnd.com/2010/09/19/1406142/caring-for-the-injured.html |title=Our War: Korea ... Belleville surgeon Dr. Bruno Kwapis rebuilt faces of war &#124; Belleville News-Democrat |publisher=Bnd.com |date=2010-09-19 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/belleville/obituary.aspx?pid=175700732 |title=Bruno W. Kwapis Obituary: View Bruno Kwapis's Obituary by Belleville News-Democrat |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> He is of Polish descent<ref>{{cite news| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/102576572.html?dids=102576572:102576572&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+17%2C+1991&author=By+Martin+Kasindorf.+STAFF+CORRESPONDENT&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=What+They're+Saying+He+Said%2C+She+Said'+chronicles+the+war+of+the+sexes+from+both+sides.+Guess+What%3A+The+viewpoints+differ.&pqatl=google | title=What They're Saying He Said, She Said' chronicles the war of the sexes from both sides. Guess What: The viewpoints differ | first=Martin | last=Kasindorf | date=February 17, 1991 | work=Newsday}}</ref> and was raised [[Catholic]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/features/columns/e3ia91b17b15e3f3af5c176436398b57481 |url-status=dead |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Martin A. |last=Grove |title=Sick of fantasies? 'Wed' offers return to reality |date=June 20, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915080908/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/features/columns/e3ia91b17b15e3f3af5c176436398b57481 |archivedate=September 15, 2007}}</ref> attending the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] preparatory academy [[St. Louis University High School]].\n\nHe earned a [[Bachelor's degree]] at [[Northwestern University]]'s School of Speech, after which he traveled west to enroll in the [[Master of Fine Arts|M.F.A.]] program at the [[USC School of Cinema-Television]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Notable Alumni |work=USC School of Cinema-Television |url=http://www-cntv.usc.edu/friends_alumni/alumni-notable.cfm |accessdate=2006-03-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060216024619/http://www-cntv.usc.edu/friends_alumni/alumni-notable.cfm |archivedate=2006-02-16 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKwapis' twenty-four-minute thesis film, ''For Heaven's Sake'', won the [[Student Academy Award]] in 1982. The film is a contemporary adaptation of [[Mozart]]'s one-act [[opera]] ''[[Der Schauspieldirektor]]'' (''The Impresario'').\n\n==Family==\nKwapis is married to [[Marisa Silver]], with whom he has two sons.<ref name=keeping>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/01/movies/01roch.html | title = Keeping Things Human Size, Despite the Stars | first = Margy | last = Rochlin | work = [[The New York Times]] | date = January 30, 2009 | accessdate = November 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=pifm>{{cite web | url = http://www.pifmagazine.com/2010/07/marisa-silver-interview/ | title = Marisa Silver | first = Derek | last = Alger | work = Pif Magazine | date = July 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1980s===\nIn 1983, Kwapis directed ''Revenge of the Nerd'' for [[CBS]]' ''Afternoon Playhouse'', followed by ''Summer Switch'' for [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''Afterschool Special''. Starring [[Robert Klein]], ''Summer Switch'' is an adaptation of the novel of the same name, the sequel to a young adult fantasy, ''[[Freaky Friday]]''. For the Scholastic Book Company, Kwapis directed his first feature film ''[[The Beniker Gang]]'', starring [[Andrew McCarthy]].\n\nKwapis' next film was ''[[Sesame Street Presents Follow That Bird]]'' ([[Warner Bros.]], 1985). The film was the big-screen debut of the [[Sesame Street]] ensemble ([[Big Bird]], [[Oscar the Grouch]], [[Count von Count|The Count]], [[Bert & Ernie]], et al.). ''Follow That Bird'' tells the story of Big Bird's quest to live with a family of his own kind; namely, birds. A social worker arranges for Big Bird to move in with a family of Dodo Birds in Oceanview, Illinois.\n\nIn 1987, Kwapis made his [[prime time]] television debut, directing an installment of [[Steven Spielberg]]'s ''[[Amazing Stories (1985 TV series)|Amazing Stories]]''.\n\nKwapis' second feature ''[[Vibes (film)|Vibes]]'' ([[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]], 1988) was made under [[Ron Howard]] and [[Brian Grazer]]'s fledgling [[Imagine Entertainment|Imagine]] banner. Written by [[Lowell Ganz]] and [[Babaloo Mandel]], ''Vibes'' is the tale of two psychics ([[Jeff Goldblum]] and [[Cyndi Lauper]]) who are enlisted by a fortune hunter ([[Peter Falk]]) to divine the whereabouts of a treasure hidden in the [[Andes]]. The film was shot on location in [[Ecuador]], and features a pan pipe-flavored score by [[James Horner]].\n\n===1990s===\nKwapis began the 1990s with a feature-film project, ''[[He Said, She Said (film)|He Said, She Said]]'' ([[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]], 1991)\u2014co-directed by his now-wife [[Marisa Silver]]. The film, written by [[Brian Hohlfeld]], is a romantic comedy in which the same events are recounted twice\u2014once from each partner's point of view. The woman's ([[Elizabeth Perkins]]) portion of the film was directed by Silver and the man's ([[Kevin Bacon]]) by Kwapis. The film also features [[Sharon Stone]] and [[Nathan Lane]]. Soon after the release of ''He Said, She Said'', the film's title (coined by Silver) entered the vernacular as shorthand for any situation involving \"testimony in direct conflict\".<ref>For the etymology of the phrase, \"He said, she said\", see William Safire, \"On Language; He-Said, She-Said\", https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/12/magazine/on-language-he-said-she-said.html .</ref>\n\nKwapis then moved into series television, directing the pilot of [[HBO]]'s comedy ''[[The Larry Sanders Show]]''. He directed twelve episodes of the series.\n\nKwapis also contributed two episodes to the sci-fi series ''[[Eerie, Indiana]]''.\n\nKwapis' fourth feature, ''[[Dunston Checks In]]'' ([[Twentieth Century Fox]], 1996), stars [[Jason Alexander]] as the manager of a grand hotel in [[New York City]], which is owned and operated by a tyrant in the [[Leona Helmsley]] mold ([[Faye Dunaway]]). An aristocrat of dubious origin ([[Rupert Everett]]) checks into the hotel with an orangutan jewel thief.\n\nKwapis' next film, ''[[The Beautician and the Beast]]'' ([[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]], 1997), evokes the Ruritanian comedies of [[Ernst Lubitsch]]. [[Fran Drescher]] plays a New York cosmetologist who is mistakenly hired to tutor the children of the despotic president of Slovetzia ([[Timothy Dalton]]).\n\nIn the late 1990s, Kwapis directed two episodes of [[NBC]]'s short-lived cult following show ''[[Freaks and Geeks]]''.\n\n===2000s===\nIn the first decade of the 2000s, Kwapis directed nineteen episodes of [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', earning a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for his work as a producer-director.\n\nIn 2001, Kwapis helped develop ''[[The Bernie Mac Show]]'' for Fox, directing the pilot and ten additional episodes, including the series finale, \"Bernie's Angels\". Also for Fox, Kwapis was one of the main creative forces behind ''[[Grounded for Life]]'', a hybrid comedy combining single- and multi-camera techniques. Kwapis experimented with the form even further in the pilot of ''[[Watching Ellie]]'', [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]]' follow-up to ''[[Seinfeld]]''. The distinctive pilot has a story that unfolds in real time, with an on-screen clock. Playing the role of Ellie's ex-boyfriend is [[Steve Carell]], with whom Kwapis would shortly collaborate on his next major project.\n\nIn 2005, Kwapis worked on ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' which was an adaptation of the [[BBC]] [[mockumentary]] of the [[The Office (UK TV series)|same name]]. He directed the [[Pilot (The Office)|pilot]] and twelve additional episodes, including the 100th episode of the series, \"Company Picnic\". His work on the third-season premiere, \"[[Gay Witch Hunt]]\", earned him a second [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]]. He also directed the [[Finale (The Office)|series finale]].\n\nFor Showtime Independent Pictures, Kwapis wrote and directed ''[[Sexual Life]]'' (2005), loosely based on [[Arthur Schnitzler]]'s satiric story taking place in [[fin-de-si\u00e8cle]] [[Vienna]], ''[[La Ronde (play)|La Ronde]]''.\n\nKwapis' next feature was another adaptation, ''[[Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]'' ([[Warner Bros.]], 2006), based on the bestselling young adult novel by [[Ann Brashares]]. ''Sisterhood'', a coming-of-age story about four sixteen-year-old friends, stars [[Amber Tamblyn]], [[Alexis Bledel]], [[America Ferrera]], and [[Blake Lively]] (her screen debut).\n\nHis next feature, ''[[License to Wed]]'' (Warner Bros., 2007), follows a young couple ([[Mandy Moore]] and [[John Krasinski]]), as they embark upon an unorthodox pre-marital course, devised by a highly mischievous and somewhat perverse minister ([[Robin Williams]]). Designed to determine their compatibility, the course compresses the first ten years of marriage into one week.\n\nKwapis' follow-up was another look at romantic entanglements, ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That into You]]'' ([[New Line Cinema]], 2009). The film is adapted from the bestselling advice book by [[Greg Behrendt]] and [[Liz Tuccillo]], which encouraged people to learn to read romantic signals correctly. The film stars [[Ben Affleck]], [[Jennifer Aniston]], [[Drew Barrymore]], [[Jennifer Connelly]], [[Kevin Connolly (actor)|Kevin Connolly]], [[Bradley Cooper]], [[Ginnifer Goodwin]], [[Scarlett Johansson]], and [[Justin Long]].\n\n===2010s===\nKwapis launched his seventh series and directed his tenth feature film in 2010. He was the executive producer and director of the pilot of ''[[Outsourced (TV series)|Outsourced]]'', a half-hour comedy for NBC. Adapted from the 2006 [[Outsourced (film)|feature film of the same name]], ''Outsourced'' tells the story of a Kansas City-based novelties company that ships all of its customer service jobs to [[India]]. The one American employee not to be fired, Todd Dempsey ([[Ben Rappaport]]), goes to [[Mumbai]] to oversee the call center.\n\nFor [[Working Title Films]], and [[Universal Pictures]], Kwapis directed the rescue adventure ''[[Big Miracle]]'', starring [[Drew Barrymore]] and [[John Krasinski]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3ia63351ea832b17bfd91d511a23a7b04c |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090609112836/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3ia63351ea832b17bfd91d511a23a7b04c |archivedate=June 9, 2009|title=Director Ken Kwapis hunts 'Whales'}}</ref> Based on a real event that took place in 1988, the film tells the tale of a small town newsman (Krasinski) and a [[Greenpeace]] volunteer (Barrymore) who are joined by rival world superpowers to save a family of [[gray whale]]s trapped in the ice of the [[Arctic Ocean]]. The film was shot during fall 2010 in Alaska and released in 2012.\n\nIn 2013, nine years after bringing the [[Pilot (The Office)|pilot]] to U.S. television, Kwapis directed the [[Finale (The Office)|series finale]] of ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]''. He also produced the half-hour [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] pilot ''[[Happyish]]'', written by [[Shalom Auslander]] and starring [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]]. The project stalled after Hoffman's death, but was eventually recast with [[Steve Coogan]]. It made its debut on Showtime in April 2015 and, in addition to producing, Kwapis directed four of its episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Friedlander|first1=Whitney|title=Showtime Cancels \u2018Happyish\u2019 After One Season|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/happyish-canceled-showtime-1201548349/|website=Variety|accessdate=2 November 2016|date=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kwapis directed the feature film ''[[A Walk in the Woods (film)|A Walk in the Woods]]'', based on the [[A Walk in the Woods (book)|bestselling travel memoir]] by [[Bill Bryson]]. The film stars [[Robert Redford]] and [[Nick Nolte]] as two old friends who decide to walk the 2,100-mile [[Appalachian Trail]]. The film, which was co-produced by Redford, also stars [[Emma Thompson]] and [[Mary Steenburgen]], and premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2015. ''A Walk in the Woods'' was released by Broad Green on September 2, 2015.\n\nRecently, Kwapis returned to single-camera half-hour comedy and directed four episodes of [[Tig Notaro]]'s semi-autobiographical [[Internet television]] series, ''[[One Mississippi (TV series)|One Mississippi]]''\u2014two per season in 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0477129/#director |title=Ken Kwapis - IMDb |publisher=imdb.com |date=1957-08-17 |accessdate=2017-09-21}}</ref> The show was produced by [[Amazon Studios]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Dominic Patten, Nellie|title=\u2018One Mississippi\u2019, \u2018I Love Dick\u2019 & \u2018Jean-Claude Van Johnson\u2019 Canceled By Amazon|url=https://deadline.com/2018/01/one-mississippi-i-love-dick-jean-claude-van-johnson-canceled-amazon-1202245153/|website=Deadline|accessdate=January 18, 2018|date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> He has also directed episodes of ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]'', a comedy starring and produced by [[Drew Barrymore]] and first released by Netflix on February 3, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/ken-kwapis/credits/182465/916115/?from=916115 |title=Ken Kwapis |website=TV Guide |orig-year=2017 |access-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n===Feature films===\n* ''[[A Walk in the Woods (film)|A Walk in the Woods]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Big Miracle]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[He's Just Not That into You (film)|He's Just Not That into You]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[License to Wed]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)|The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Sexual Life]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Beautician and the Beast]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Dunston Checks In]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[He Said, She Said (film)|He Said, She Said]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Vibes (film)|Vibes]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Sesame Street Presents Follow That Bird]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[The Beniker Gang]]'' (1985)\n\n===Notable episodic television work (directing)===\n{{Div col}}\n*''The Dangerous Book for Boys'' (2018)\n*''Santa Clarita Diet'' (2017-)\n*''One Mississippi'' (2016-2017)\n*''Happyish'' (2015)\n*''The Office'' (2005-2013)\n*''Outsourced'' (2010)\n*''Parks and Recreation'' (2010)\n*''The Bernie Mac Show'' (2001-2006)\n*''Malcolm in the Middle'' (2000-2004)\n*''Watching Ellie'' (2002)\n*''Grounded for Life'' (2001)\n*''ER'' (1999-2000)\n*''Freaks and Geeks'' (1999-2000)\n*''The Wonderful World of Disney'' (1998)\n*''Bakersfield P.D.'' (1993)\n*''The Larry Sanders Show'' (1992-1993)\n*''Eerie, Indiana'' (1992)\n*''Amazing Stories'' (1987)\n*''ABC Afterschool Specials'' (1984)\n*''CBS Afternoon Playhouse'' (1983)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0477129|Ken Kwapis}}\n\n{{Ken Kwapis}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kwapis, Ken}}\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Illinois]]\n[[Category:People from Belleville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University School of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "DodgeBoy102", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ken_Kwapis"}
