{"title_page": "Tony Zosherafatain", "text_new": "'''Tony Zosherafatain''' (born December 21, 1987) is an American [[Film director|director]], producer, and [[writer]] from [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]. He openly identifies as a [[transgender]] man and has directed and produced award-winning films about trans identity. As a documentarian, his films utilize a character-driven lens to portray [[Transidentity|trans identity]], [[intersectionality]], [[civil and political rights]], and [[political movements]]. He is the current [[Film director|Director]] of ''[https://www.transintrumpland.com/ Trans in Trumpland,]'' a forthcoming documentary about the [[Trump (president)|Trump]] administration's impact on transgender [[Americans]]. The film is produced through [https://www.transwavefilms.com TransWave Films], a production company run by Zosherafatain and fellow trans filmmaker Jamie DiNicola, and is supported by Executive Producer [[Miss Major Griffin-Gracy]]. [[Jason B. Kohl]] serves as Lead Editor of ''Trans in Trumpland'' alongside [[Tchavdar Georgiev]] as Consulting Editor. After a successful [[Kickstarter]] campaign<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/transintrumpland/trans-in-trumpland/description|title=Trans in Trumpland Kickstarter|last=|first=|date=|website=Kickstarter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and media coverage by [[GLAAD]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-wrap-trailers-now-apocalypse-and-billions-critics-choice-award-winners-and-more|title=The GLAAD Wrap: Trailers for 'Now Apocalypse' and 'Billions,' Critics' Choice Award winners, and more!|date=2019-01-17|website=GLAAD|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>, the film completed production in 2019 and is in post-production.<ref>{{Citation|title=Trans in Trumpland|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt9163946/|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nTony began his film career in 2012 after realizing that there weren't many films about transgender stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm8697282/|title=Tony Zosherafatain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> His current and prior films include ''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt12079070/?ref_=nm_knf_t1 Finding Cedar,] [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11056716/?ref_=nm_knf_t4 Fratello], [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6407488/?ref_=nm_knf_t3 I am Isak,] and [https://www.transwavefilms.com/venture-out Venture Out]''. Venture Out was selected for distribution by [[Recreational Equipment, Inc.|REI]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rei.com/blog/hike/rei-presents-venture-out|title=REI Presents: Venture Out|last=Staff|first=R. E. I.|date=2020-02-20|website=REI Co-op Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> His films have screened at domestic and international [[Film festival|film festivals,]] including [[Inside Out Film and Video Festival|Inside Out]], [https://www.theemerginglens.com Emerging Lens], Thessaloniki LGBT Film Festival<ref>{{Citation|title=I am Isak|url=https://www.filmfestival.gr/en/movie/movie/7546|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>, and [[Shanghai Queer Film Festival]]. He was the recipient of a Finalist Award at Emerging Lens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theemerginglens.com/awards|title=2017 AWARD WINNERS...|website=emerginglens|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nHis writing blends his identity background, personal anecdotes, and commentary on societal issues to reflect on modern [[American society]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nixon|first=Paul G.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NR0xDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT109&lpg=PT109&dq=tony+zosherafatain+writer&source=bl&ots=qaYbEi2c1m&sig=ACfU3U1sWpkoRaeFCvVAF6WIilPXZR7wpg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1sMalpu7oAhVUhHIEHSLxAog4ChDoATABegQICxAo#v=onepage&q=tony%20zosherafatain%20writer&f=false|title=Sex in the Digital Age|last2=D\u00fcsterh\u00f6ft|first2=Isabel K.|date=2017-08-16|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-315-44622-6|language=en}}</ref> He began writing for the [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/author/anthony-zosherafatain|title=Tony Zosherafatain {{!}} HuffPost|website=www.huffpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> after realizing he faced unique challenges as a transgender [[Iranian Americans|Iranian-American.]] After releasing an article entitled \"I\u2019m Iranian-American. This Is What Trump\u2019s America Feels Like\", he was published on the [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/im-iranian-american-this-is-what-trumps-america_b_58a49fb3e4b0cd37efcfefd5|title=I'm Iranian-American. This Is What Trump's America Feels Like.|last=Zosherafatain|first=Tony|last2=filmmaker|first2=ContributorI'm a|date=2017-02-15|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Writer|first3=A.|last4=Immigrants|first4=The Son of|last5=Person|first5=A. Progress-Minded}}</ref>, [[Thought Catalog]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thoughtcatalog.com/tony-zosherafatain/2017/03/im-iranian-american-and-this-is-what-trumps-america-feels-like-to-me/|title=I\u2019m Iranian-American And This Is What Trump\u2019s America Feels Like To Me|date=2017-03-28|website=Thought Catalog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and [[Medium (website)|Medium.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.politicsmeanspolitics.com/im-iranian-american-this-is-what-trump-s-america-feels-like-7345e666b6b8|title=I\u2019m Iranian-American. This Is What Trump\u2019s America Feels Like.|last=Zosherafatain|first=Tony|date=2017-02-20|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He appeared in [[Mark Seliger]]'s book ''[https://www.rizzoliusa.com/book/9780847858316/ On Christopher Street: Transgender Stories]'' and was featured in the [[The New York Times|New York Times]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Jacob|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/29/style/transgender-christopher-street-photography-book-mark-seliger.html|title=A Trans Life, Captured by Mark Seliger|date=2016-09-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate (LGBT magazine).]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/books/2016/10/04/transgender-stories-christopher-street-photos|title=Transgender Stories on Christopher Street (Photos)|date=2016-10-04|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In 2015, he was part of a series of portraits of the trans community published in [[The New Yorker|The New Yorker.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/photo-booth/transgender-portraits-and-the-things-a-body-wont-tell|title=Transgender Portraits and the Things a Body Won\u2019t Tell|last=Weinstein|first=Michael M.|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He shared his reflections and wisdom for trans youth in a [[BuzzFeed]] article<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/skarlan/you-are-loved|title=What Trans Youth Need To Hear Right Now, According To Trans Adults|last=Karlan|first=Sarah|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> and his discussion of what it's like to wear a chest binder appeared in a [[BuzzFeed]] short film.<ref>{{Citation|title=BuzzFeed LGBTQ on Facebook Watch|url=https://www.facebook.com/BuzzFeedLGBTQ/videos/what-its-like-to-wear-a-chest-binder/844538515673335/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In 2016, he advocated to increase accessibility to [[gender affirmation surgery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/53g5aq/the-organization-that-wants-to-make-gender-affirmation-surgery-easier|title=The Organization That Wants to Make Gender Affirmation Surgery Easier|last=Hope|first=Allison|date=2016-12-09|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> His transition and personal journey towards self acceptance was portrayed in an online [[BBC]] video series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/magazine-34884494/trans-man-learning-to-love-my-body|title=Trans man: 'Learning to love my body'|website=BBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nZosherafatain was born in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], the oldest of two. He was assigned female at birth and born to an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] father and a [[Greeks|Greek]] mother. His father is originally from [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] and his mother is from [[Ganochora]], [[Greece]]. Due to the [[Iranian Revolution]], his father had to escape from Iran, and his mother left a farming village in [[Greece]] in search of a better life. He has a younger sibling named [[Aristotle|Aristotle.]] Both siblings are first-generation Americans. He spent most of his life in [[Reading, Massachusetts]], and played ice hockey as his main sport. In middle school, he would frequently borrow his family's [[camcorder]] to film his neighborhood friends playing pranks.\n\nAfter spending one year at [[Reading Memorial High School]], he transferred to [[Tabor Academy (Massachusetts)]] as a sophomore. After graduating with honors from Tabor, he was accepted to [[Wesleyan University]] where he pursued student government, film making, activism, and writing. He was a [[Watson Fellow]] finalist in his senior year at Wesleyan for his proposal to produce a documentary about transgender identity across diverse cultural settings. Upon his graduation from Wesleyan in 2010, he went on to attend [[New York University]] and moved to [[New York City]] to begin his film career.\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Short films ===\n* ''Fratello'' (2019)\n* ''Venture Out'' (2020)\n\n=== Short documentaries ===\n* ''I am Isak'' (2017)\n* ''Call me Kye'' (2019)\n* ''Finding Cedar'' (2020)\n\n=== Feature documentaries ===\n* ''Trans in Trumpland'' (2020)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zosherafatain, Tony}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Tony Zosherafatain''' (born December 21, 1987) is an American [[Film director|director]], producer, and [[writer]] from [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]]. He openly identifies as a [[transgender]] man and has directed and produced award-winning films about trans identity. As a documentarian, his films utilize a character-driven lens to portray [[Transidentity|trans identity]], [[intersectionality]], [[civil and political rights]], and [[political movements]]. He is the current [[Film director|Director]] of ''[https://www.transintrumpland.com/ Trans in Trumpland,]'' a forthcoming documentary about the [[Trump (president)|Trump]] administration's impact on transgender [[Americans]]. The film is produced through [https://www.transwavefilms.com TransWave Films], a production company run by Zosherafatain and fellow trans filmmaker [http://www.jamiedinicola.com Jamie DiNicola] and is supported by Executive Producer [[Miss Major Griffin-Gracy]]. [[Jason B. Kohl]] serves as Lead Editor of ''Trans in Trumpland'' alongside [[Tchavdar Georgiev]] as Consulting Editor. After a successful [[Kickstarter]] campaign<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/transintrumpland/trans-in-trumpland/description|title=Trans in Trumpland Kickstarter|last=|first=|date=|website=Kickstarter|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and media coverage by [[GLAAD]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-wrap-trailers-now-apocalypse-and-billions-critics-choice-award-winners-and-more|title=The GLAAD Wrap: Trailers for 'Now Apocalypse' and 'Billions,' Critics' Choice Award winners, and more!|date=2019-01-17|website=GLAAD|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>, the film completed production in 2019 and is in post-production.<ref>{{Citation|title=Trans in Trumpland|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt9163946/|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nTony began his film career in 2012 after realizing that there weren't many films about transgender stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm8697282/|title=Tony Zosherafatain|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> His current and prior films include ''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt12079070/?ref_=nm_knf_t1 Finding Cedar,] [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11056716/?ref_=nm_knf_t4 Fratello], [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6407488/?ref_=nm_knf_t3 I am Isak,] and [https://www.transwavefilms.com/venture-out Venture Out]''. Venture Out was selected for distribution by [[Recreational Equipment, Inc.|REI]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rei.com/blog/hike/rei-presents-venture-out|title=REI Presents: Venture Out|last=Staff|first=R. E. I.|date=2020-02-20|website=REI Co-op Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> His films have screened at domestic and international [[Film festival|film festivals,]] including [[Inside Out Film and Video Festival|Inside Out]], [https://www.theemerginglens.com Emerging Lens], Thessaloniki LGBT Film Festival<ref>{{Citation|title=I am Isak|url=https://www.filmfestival.gr/en/movie/movie/7546|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>, and [[Shanghai Queer Film Festival]]. He was the recipient of a Finalist Award at Emerging Lens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theemerginglens.com/awards|title=2017 AWARD WINNERS...|website=emerginglens|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nHis writing blends his identity background, personal anecdotes, and commentary on societal issues to reflect on modern [[American society]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nixon|first=Paul G.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NR0xDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT109&lpg=PT109&dq=tony+zosherafatain+writer&source=bl&ots=qaYbEi2c1m&sig=ACfU3U1sWpkoRaeFCvVAF6WIilPXZR7wpg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj1sMalpu7oAhVUhHIEHSLxAog4ChDoATABegQICxAo#v=onepage&q=tony%20zosherafatain%20writer&f=false|title=Sex in the Digital Age|last2=D\u00fcsterh\u00f6ft|first2=Isabel K.|date=2017-08-16|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-315-44622-6|language=en}}</ref> He began writing for the [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/author/anthony-zosherafatain|title=Tony Zosherafatain {{!}} HuffPost|website=www.huffpost.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> after realizing he faced unique challenges as a transgender [[Iranian Americans|Iranian-American.]] After releasing an article entitled \"I\u2019m Iranian-American. This Is What Trump\u2019s America Feels Like\", he was published on the [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/im-iranian-american-this-is-what-trumps-america_b_58a49fb3e4b0cd37efcfefd5|title=I'm Iranian-American. This Is What Trump's America Feels Like.|last=Zosherafatain|first=Tony|last2=filmmaker|first2=ContributorI'm a|date=2017-02-15|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Writer|first3=A.|last4=Immigrants|first4=The Son of|last5=Person|first5=A. Progress-Minded}}</ref>, [[Thought Catalog]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thoughtcatalog.com/tony-zosherafatain/2017/03/im-iranian-american-and-this-is-what-trumps-america-feels-like-to-me/|title=I\u2019m Iranian-American And This Is What Trump\u2019s America Feels Like To Me|date=2017-03-28|website=Thought Catalog|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and [[Medium (website)|Medium.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.politicsmeanspolitics.com/im-iranian-american-this-is-what-trump-s-america-feels-like-7345e666b6b8|title=I\u2019m Iranian-American. This Is What Trump\u2019s America Feels Like.|last=Zosherafatain|first=Tony|date=2017-02-20|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He appeared in [[Mark Seliger]]'s book ''[https://www.rizzoliusa.com/book/9780847858316/ On Christopher Street: Transgender Stories]'' and was featured in the [[The New York Times|New York Times]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Jacob|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/29/style/transgender-christopher-street-photography-book-mark-seliger.html|title=A Trans Life, Captured by Mark Seliger|date=2016-09-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and [[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate (LGBT magazine).]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/books/2016/10/04/transgender-stories-christopher-street-photos|title=Transgender Stories on Christopher Street (Photos)|date=2016-10-04|website=www.advocate.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In 2015, he was part of a series of portraits of the trans community published in [[The New Yorker|The New Yorker.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/photo-booth/transgender-portraits-and-the-things-a-body-wont-tell|title=Transgender Portraits and the Things a Body Won\u2019t Tell|last=Weinstein|first=Michael M.|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> He shared his reflections and wisdom for trans youth in a [[BuzzFeed]] article<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/skarlan/you-are-loved|title=What Trans Youth Need To Hear Right Now, According To Trans Adults|last=Karlan|first=Sarah|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> and his discussion of what it's like to wear a chest binder appeared in a [[BuzzFeed]] short film.<ref>{{Citation|title=BuzzFeed LGBTQ on Facebook Watch|url=https://www.facebook.com/BuzzFeedLGBTQ/videos/what-its-like-to-wear-a-chest-binder/844538515673335/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> In 2016, he advocated to increase accessibility to [[gender affirmation surgery]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/53g5aq/the-organization-that-wants-to-make-gender-affirmation-surgery-easier|title=The Organization That Wants to Make Gender Affirmation Surgery Easier|last=Hope|first=Allison|date=2016-12-09|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> His transition and personal journey towards self acceptance was portrayed in an online [[BBC]] video series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/magazine-34884494/trans-man-learning-to-love-my-body|title=Trans man: 'Learning to love my body'|website=BBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nZosherafatain was born in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], the oldest of two. He was assigned female at birth and born to an [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] father and a [[Greeks|Greek]] mother. His father is originally from [[Tehran]], [[Iran]] and his mother is from [[Ganochora]], [[Greece]]. Due to the [[Iranian Revolution]], his father had to escape from Iran, and his mother left a farming village in [[Greece]] in search of a better life. He has a younger sibling named [[Aristotle|Aristotle.]] Both siblings are first-generation Americans. He spent most of his life in [[Reading, Massachusetts]], and played ice hockey as his main sport. In middle school, he would frequently borrow his family's [[camcorder]] to film his neighborhood friends playing pranks.\n\nAfter spending one year at [[Reading Memorial High School]], he transferred to [[Tabor Academy (Massachusetts)]] as a sophomore. After graduating with honors from Tabor, he was accepted to [[Wesleyan University]] where he pursued student government, film making, activism, and writing. He was a [[Watson Fellow]] finalist in his senior year at Wesleyan for his proposal to produce a documentary about transgender identity across diverse cultural settings. Upon his graduation from Wesleyan in 2010, he went on to attend [[New York University]] and moved to [[New York City]] to begin his film career.\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Short films ===\n* ''Fratello'' (2019)\n* ''Venture Out'' (2020)\n\n=== Short documentaries ===\n* ''I am Isak'' (2017)\n* ''Call me Kye'' (2019)\n* ''Finding Cedar'' (2020)\n\n=== Feature documentaries ===\n* ''Trans in Trumpland'' (2020)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zosherafatain, Tony}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "JDassistant", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed external link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Zosherafatain"}
{"title_page": "George Loveridge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = George Loveridge\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| nickname = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1890|10|15|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[New Plymouth]], New Zealand\n| death_place = New Plymouth, New Zealand\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1970|11|28|1890|10|15|df=yes}}\n| ru_position = [[Rugby union positions#Wing|Wing three-quarter]]\n| height = {{convert|5|ft|7+1/4|in|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=\"Military record\">{{cite web |url=http://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE19928449 |title=Loveridge, George - WWI 10498, WWII 804939 - Army |date= |website= |publisher=Archives New Zealand |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|149|lb|kg|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=\"Military record\"/>\n| allblackid = 510\n| allblackno = 206\n| ru_nationalteam = {{nowrap|{{ru|New Zealand|noflag=1}}}}\n| ru_nationalyears = 1913\u201314\n| ru_nationalcaps = 0\n| ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n| ru_province = {{Rut Taranaki}}\n| ru_provinceyears = 1912\u201315\n| ru_provincecaps = 16\n| ru_provincepoints = \n| occupation = Public servant\n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = }}\n\n'''George Loveridge''' (15 October 1890 \u2013 28 November 1970) was a New Zealand [[rugby union]] player. A [[Rugby union positions#Wing|wing three-quarter]], Loveridge represented {{Rut Taranaki}} at a provincial level, and was a member of the New Zealand national side, the [[All Blacks]], in 1913 and 1914. He played 11 matches for the All Blacks but did not appear in any internationals.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://stats.allblacks.com/asp/Profile.asp?ABID=510 |title = Geo Loveridge | last = Knight | first = Lindsay | publisher = New Zealand Rugby Union | accessdate = 28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Loveridge\u2014a telegraphist before the war\u2014served overseas as a sapper with the New Zealand Field Engineers from 1916 to 1919. He served again during [[World War II]] as a sergeant with 2nd Battalion Taranaki Regiment, carrying out administrative duties in New Zealand between 1942 and 1943.<ref name=\"Military record\"/>\n\nGeorge's cousin, [[Norm Loveridge]], represented New Zealand at rugby league.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loveridge, George}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rugby union players from New Plymouth]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby union players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Taranaki rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union wings]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War II]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-rugbyunion-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox rugby biography \n| name = George Loveridge\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| caption = \n| nickname = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1890|10|15|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = [[New Plymouth]], New Zealand\n| death_place = New Plymouth, New Zealand\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1970|11|28|1890|10|15|df=yes}}\n| ru_position = [[Rugby union positions#Wing|Wing three-quarter]]\n| height = {{convert|5|ft|7+1/4|in|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=\"Military record\">{{cite web |url=http://ndhadeliver.natlib.govt.nz/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE19928449 |title=Loveridge, George - WWI 10498, WWII 804939 - Army |date= |website= |publisher=Archives New Zealand |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|149|lb|kg|abbr=on|order=flip}}<ref name=\"Military record\"/>\n| allblackid = 510\n| allblackno = 206\n| ru_nationalteam = {{nowrap|{{ru|New Zealand|noflag=1}}}}\n| ru_nationalyears = 1913\u201314\n| ru_nationalcaps = 0\n| ru_nationalpoints = (0)\n| ru_province = {{Rut Taranaki}}\n| ru_provinceyears = 1912\u201315\n| ru_provincecaps = 16\n| ru_provincepoints = \n| occupation = Public servant\n| family = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| relatives = \n| school = \n| university = }}\n\n'''George Loveridge''' (15 October 1890 \u2013 28 November 1970) was a New Zealand [[rugby union]] player. A [[Rugby union positions#Wing|wing three-quarter]], Loveridge represented {{Rut Taranaki}} at a provincial level, and was a member of the New Zealand national side, the [[All Blacks]], in 1913 and 1914. He played 11 matches for the All Blacks but did not appear in any internationals.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://stats.allblacks.com/asp/Profile.asp?ABID=510 |title = Geo Loveridge | last = Knight | first = Lindsay | publisher = New Zealand Rugby Union | accessdate = 28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], Loveridge\u2014a telegraphist before the war\u2014served overseas as a sapper with the New Zealand Field Engineers from 1916 to 1919. He served again during [[World War II]] as a sergeant with 2nd Battalion Taranaki Regiment, carrying out administrative duties in New Zealand between 1942 and 1943.<ref name=\"Military record\"/>\n\nGeorge's cousin, [[Norman Loveridge]], represented New Zealand at rugby league.\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loveridge, George}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rugby union players from New Plymouth]]\n[[Category:New Zealand rugby union players]]\n[[Category:New Zealand international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Taranaki rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Rugby union wings]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:New Zealand military personnel of World War II]]\n\n\n{{NewZealand-rugbyunion-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Grutness", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Loveridge"}
{"title_page": "Mutsumi Tamabayashi", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name=Mutsumi Tamabayashi\n|fullname=Mutsumi Tamabayashi\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1984|10|12}}\n|birth_place=[[Uwajima, Ehime]], Japan\n|height={{height|m=1.78}}\n|position=[[Defender (association football)|Full-back]]\n|currentclub=[[Ehime FC]]\n|clubnumber=3\n|youthyears1=2000\u20132002 |youthclubs1=Minamiuwa Senior High School\n|youthyears2=2003\u20132006 |youthclubs2=Kibi International University \n|years1=2007\u20132009 |clubs1=[[Fagiano Okayama]] |caps1=48 |goals1=1\n|years2=2010\u20132014 |clubs2=[[Matsumoto Yamaga]] |caps2=125 |goals2=7\n|years3=2015\u2013 |clubs3=[[Ehime FC]] |caps3 = 106 |goals3 = 5\n|club-update=1 January 2019\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Mutsumi Tamabayashi'''|\u7389\u6797 \u7766\u5b9f|Tamabayashi Mutsumi|born October 12, 1984}} is a Japanese [[Association football|football]] player for [[Ehime FC]].\n\n==Club statistics==\n''Updated to end of 2018 season''.<ref>Nippon Sports Kikaku Publishing inc./\u65e5\u672c\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u4f01\u753b\u51fa\u7248\u793e, [https://www.amazon.co.jp/J1-J3%E9%81%B8%E6%89%8B%E5%90%8D%E9%91%91%E3%83%8F%E3%83%B3%E3%83%87%E3%82%A3%E7%89%88-2018-NSK-MOOK/dp/4905411521 \"J1&J2&J3\u9078\u624b\u540d\u9451\u30cf\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3\u7248 2018 (NSK MOOK)\"], 7 February 2018, Japan, {{ISBN|978-4905411529}} (p. 211 out of 289)</ref><ref>Nippon Sports Kikaku Publishing inc./\u65e5\u672c\u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\u4f01\u753b\u51fa\u7248\u793e, [https://www.amazon.co.jp/2017-J1-J3%E9%81%B8%E6%89%8B%E5%90%8D%E9%91%91-NSK-MOOK/dp/4905411424/ref=pd_sim_14_1/356-9491148-0114816?_encoding=UTF8&psc=1&refRID=BA8BN4Y0F97GNWKQM78H \"2017 J1&J2&J3\u9078\u624b\u540d\u9451 (NSK MOOK)\"], 8 February 2017, Japan, {{ISBN|978-4905411420}} (p. 191 out of 289)</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | Tot